ds and their fruits. Thus, those who have become humans may inflict numerous torments of the Reviving Hell, such as the pains of being crushed between trees, being torn to pieces, bending down, being a road, being taken on the path of a ruler, the sensation of earth, falling, being pierced by needles, being pulled by a rope, falling off an elephant, being in a sandstorm, being hit by clubs, flogging, headaches, being squeezed like an infant or child on the lap, feeling hot or cold, feeling wet, having water poured on one’s body, being hung on a pole, being crushed in a ravine or an abyss, being seized by enemies, having one’s genitals cut off, having one’s fingers cut off, having one’s body hair plucked out, being fooled, being submerged in boiling lead and copper, having one’s nose pierced by sharp iron, snakes entering one’s private parts, being hit by boulders, developing craving, being swathed in garlands of fire, having one’s hair torn out, falling prey to biting insects, having one’s skin cut, confinement, having one’s body cut, being cooked in a jar or pot, being burned like bricks, having salt rubbed into open wounds, being swept with a broom, being burned, having one’s big toes amputated and burned, ingesting long chili peppers, ingesting the froth of thirty seas, being struck by hands and feet, moving far away, having one’s molar teeth extracted, being burned by oil, being beaten like gold, severe swelling, and rising and falling. All these many different kinds of painful tortures will, upon separating from one’s body, lead to a hideous fall into the lower realms, and so, in the hell of Relentless Torments one will experience effects concomitant with their causes. Yet for the beings in that realm of hell the ripening is incomparably more severe, as the harms that were mentioned earlier are here multiplied a hundred billion times. Such is the way that beings come to directly experience the effects of their own actions."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"38:T884,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“How does the monk concern himself with Relentless Torments, the fourth realm that neighbors the Reviving Hell? The karmic ripening of cause and effect accords with the relationship between seeds and their fruits. Thus, those who have become humans may inflict numerous torments of the Reviving Hell, such as the pains of being crushed between trees, being torn to pieces, bending down, being a road, being taken on the path of a ruler, the sensation of earth, falling, being pierced by needles, being pulled by a rope, falling off an elephant, being in a sandstorm, being hit by clubs, flogging, headaches, being squeezed like an infant or child on the lap, feeling hot or cold, feeling wet, having water poured on one’s body, being hung on a pole, being crushed in a ravine or an abyss, being seized by enemies, having one’s genitals cut off, having one’s fingers cut off, having one’s body hair plucked out, being fooled, being submerged in boiling lead and copper, having one’s nose pierced by sharp iron, snakes entering one’s private parts, being hit by boulders, developing craving, being swathed in garlands of fire, having one’s hair torn out, falling prey to biting insects, having one’s skin cut, confinement, having one’s body cut, being cooked in a jar or pot, being burned like bricks, having salt rubbed into open wounds, being swept with a broom, being burned, having one’s big toes amputated and burned, ingesting long chili peppers, ingesting the froth of thirty seas, being struck by hands and feet, moving far away, having one’s molar teeth extracted, being burned by oil, being beaten like gold, severe swelling, and rising and falling. All these many different kinds of painful tortures will, upon separating from one’s body, lead to a hideous fall into the lower realms, and so, in the hell of Relentless Torments one will experience effects concomitant with their causes. Yet for the beings in that realm of hell the ripening is incomparably more severe, as the harms that were mentioned earlier are here multiplied a hundred billion times. Such is the way that beings come to directly experience the effects of their own actions."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"39:T884,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“How does the monk concern himself with Relentless Torments, the fourth realm that neighbors the Reviving Hell? The karmic ripening of cause and effect accords with the relationship between seeds and their fruits. Thus, those who have become humans may inflict numerous torments of the Reviving Hell, such as the pains of being crushed between trees, being torn to pieces, bending down, being a road, being taken on the path of a ruler, the sensation of earth, falling, being pierced by needles, being pulled by a rope, falling off an elephant, being in a sandstorm, being hit by clubs, flogging, headaches, being squeezed like an infant or child on the lap, feeling hot or cold, feeling wet, having water poured on one’s body, being hung on a pole, being crushed in a ravine or an abyss, being seized by enemies, having one’s genitals cut off, having one’s fingers cut off, having one’s body hair plucked out, being fooled, being submerged in boiling lead and copper, having one’s nose pierced by sharp iron, snakes entering one’s private parts, being hit by boulders, developing craving, being swathed in garlands of fire, having one’s hair torn out, falling prey to biting insects, having one’s skin cut, confinement, having one’s body cut, being cooked in a jar or pot, being burned like bricks, having salt rubbed into open wounds, being swept with a broom, being burned, having one’s big toes amputated and burned, ingesting long chili peppers, ingesting the froth of thirty seas, being struck by hands and feet, moving far away, having one’s molar teeth extracted, being burned by oil, being beaten like gold, severe swelling, and rising and falling. All these many different kinds of painful tortures will, upon separating from one’s body, lead to a hideous fall into the lower realms, and so, in the hell of Relentless Torments one will experience effects concomitant with their causes. Yet for the beings in that realm of hell the ripening is incomparably more severe, as the harms that were mentioned earlier are here multiplied a hundred billion times. Such is the way that beings come to directly experience the effects of their own actions."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"3a:T884,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“How does the monk concern himself with Relentless Torments, the fourth realm that neighbors the Reviving Hell? The karmic ripening of cause and effect accords with the relationship between seeds and their fruits. Thus, those who have become humans may inflict numerous torments of the Reviving Hell, such as the pains of being crushed between trees, being torn to pieces, bending down, being a road, being taken on the path of a ruler, the sensation of earth, falling, being pierced by needles, being pulled by a rope, falling off an elephant, being in a sandstorm, being hit by clubs, flogging, headaches, being squeezed like an infant or child on the lap, feeling hot or cold, feeling wet, having water poured on one’s body, being hung on a pole, being crushed in a ravine or an abyss, being seized by enemies, having one’s genitals cut off, having one’s fingers cut off, having one’s body hair plucked out, being fooled, being submerged in boiling lead and copper, having one’s nose pierced by sharp iron, snakes entering one’s private parts, being hit by boulders, developing craving, being swathed in garlands of fire, having one’s hair torn out, falling prey to biting insects, having one’s skin cut, confinement, having one’s body cut, being cooked in a jar or pot, being burned like bricks, having salt rubbed into open wounds, being swept with a broom, being burned, having one’s big toes amputated and burned, ingesting long chili peppers, ingesting the froth of thirty seas, being struck by hands and feet, moving far away, having one’s molar teeth extracted, being burned by oil, being beaten like gold, severe swelling, and rising and falling. All these many different kinds of painful tortures will, upon separating from one’s body, lead to a hideous fall into the lower realms, and so, in the hell of Relentless Torments one will experience effects concomitant with their causes. Yet for the beings in that realm of hell the ripening is incomparably more severe, as the harms that were mentioned earlier are here multiplied a hundred billion times. Such is the way that beings come to directly experience the effects of their own actions."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"3b:T5f5,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“The monk will then further examine the regions that surround the Black Line Hell, wondering what other realms may be found there. Thus, he will perceive a hell realm known as Very Violent. Wondering what karmic actions may lead to birth in that hell, he will notice how certain undeserving householders secretly enjoy medical supplies and health facilities. As they deceive others, they may cause cattle to be killed. They may give false pretexts related to the gods, or engage in the negative acts of greedy brahmins. When they later separate from their bodies, they will suffer a downfall into the lower realms, taking birth in the hell known as Very Violent. There they will have their eyes plucked out by raging ravens, vultures, and wild boars. The grunts of frantic boars will be heard. The terrors of that realm also include the clubs, blazing fires, and the horrifying fierce guardians of hell. As they take birth in that realm of Very Violent, sentient beings will have their eyes, tongues, and major and minor body parts cut out, and they will be boiled alive in iron cauldrons filled with molten copper. Their bodies will be impaled, and their legs cut off. Ravens will eat from them and they will be haunted by all manner of disease. Until they have overcome, relinquished, and exhausted their evil acts, they will remain in that unbearable state of hell for many hundreds of thousands of years. Knowing neither protector nor friend, they will cry, while being slaughtered by the henchmen of the Lord of Death."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"3c:T56f,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“When the beings of that hell realm are caught by the Lord of Death’s henchmen, who are intent on impaling them on flaming stakes, they will fight both the henchmen and each other, screaming in distress. Thrown into cauldrons of boiling, molten copper, their bodies will flare up like dry wood, and thus they will panic and burn. As they are carried off by the river Filled with Stakes, some will flare up like dry grass, others will sink into the river like heavy stones, and some will wash up on the shores like mussel shells. Some bodies will melt like balls of butter, while others will first become like red-hot iron and then split into hundreds or thousands of pieces, as when a handful of sand is thrown into the air. Some will be burned up by acid, or dissolve in boiling copper or iron. Some will be caught by flaming pliers and then killed by razor-sharp weapons. Some will be killed by having their limbs pulled apart like woven fabric and some will be killed by being held face-down. Some will be caught and put in a jar, and then stewed in that jar like peas that first float on the surface and then gradually sink. Occasionally one of them will surface and moan, while others may surface in groups, moaning and clutching onto one another. Without any protector, some of them will be caught upon a burning surface, and then eaten by flaming vultures, ravens, foxes, or dogs."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"3d:T68e,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“The force of resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing acts of sexual misconduct will make one perceive females in the forest of sword-like leaves. The power of resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing acts of taking what was not given will, on the other hand, make one proceed to other regions of hell. There is a river known as Infinite Shores that flows with boiling molten copper. Upon the far shores of this river the beings of this hell will perceive abundant food, drink, and lodging. The land appears delightful, with ample shade, lush forests, streaming rivers, and cool ponds. When they see this, the beings of this hell will run toward it as before, yelling and calling upon each other, ‘Friends, come forth! Come forth, and you shall find excellent food, drink, lodging … and so forth.’ As they hear these words, other beings of this hell will also hasten forth, for they yearn for help, protection, and relief. As they meet together on the riverbank, the beings who were called will ask, ‘Where is that place, friends, where we were going to find happiness and relief?’ Then the beings who had called them will point at the opposite bank and say, ‘Friends, look at the far banks of Infinite Shores, abounding with food, drink, beds, couches, groves, forests … and so forth!’ Pushing against each other, all of them will then plunge into the river’s fierce and frothing waves of boiling metal. As they fall into the river, some will melt as if they were lumps of butter, some will be eaten by crows with flaming beaks, and some will be swallowed by fish whose flaming mouths will consume all their organs and body parts."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"3e:T518,“Lying is a tremendously negative factor that intensifies the tortures that must otherwise be endured as the result of negative actions. A completed act of lying will cut asunder one’s supportive roots of virtue, and effects always manifest in accordance with their causes. Produced by these causes, the suffering endured in the hell of Boundless Torture cannot be put into words. Unmatched by those of any other hell being, the tortures of an evil speaker of lies will include being attacked by parasites; being tortured by parasites; thirst and hunger; despair; endless suffering in utter darkness; mutual striking; experiencing terrible sounds, textures, tastes, forms, and smells; being struck by the weapons of enemies and adversaries who remember past lives; drowning in a river of acid; being stabbed with spikes; having one’s head burned by fire; being scythed down like crops; being struck by vajras; and being burned in an all-encompassing conflagration and in forest-consuming flames. These and other such hellish tortures will continue to appear for the beings in the realm of Boundless Torture, until finally their misdeeds of lying have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted. Such are the effects of the abysmal misdeed of lying as they manifest in the hell of Boundless Torture.3f:T525,“Once they escape this flaming wheel, they will again perceive their parents, friends, and loved ones. Yearning for safety, refuge, and protection, they will press on toward them. But now their path will be full of spikes produced by karmic action, and they will encounter tigers, also produced by karmic action, that will sink their fangs into them. When they tear themselves away from the tigers’ jaws, they will run, fully conscious, while the flaming sharp spikes lacerate them. The feet and legs of the hell beings to be cut, slashed, severed, and scorched. Their limbs and organs will be penetrated and torn asunder, and their bodies will burn and be completely decimated, including their veins, sinews, bones, and all the other remaining parts of their bodies. Such are the effects that accord with resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing the causal actions of lying. In this way, those who claim to speak truthfully yet misinform, deceive, and mislead others will have to watch their parents, friends, and loved ones suffer. Thus, the tortures associated with lying are fierce, excruciating, and infinite. Until the relevant negative acts have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted, the beings of this hell will be burned, boiled, cut, and killed for many hundreds of thousands of years.40:T40b,“As the monk who has knowledge of the effects of the ripening of karmic actions continues to examine the regions that surround the Great Howling Hell, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and thus perceive a neighboring hell known as No Hope of Joy. Inquiring into what karmic actions may cause one to be born there, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and see that such a birth is, in the same way as before, caused by resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing acts of killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, and alcohol consumption. As for lying, some people make false promises to donate wealth and material goods to those who suffer and who are ill, sickly, hungry, dejected, unprotected, or destitute. Thus, not living up to their promises, they fail to supply the needy with rice meals, drinks, clothing, bedding, or housing, and so they cause others to lose all hope. When such people later separate from their bodies, they will fall into the lower realms, taking birth in the hell of No Hope of Joy.41:T49c,“Once they are free from this hell, they will perceive an acid river known as The Hour of Death. The hell beings there yearn for protection and refuge, and are oppressed and terrified by the Lord of Death’s henchmen. Thus, upon seeing the river they will haul their ruined bodies toward it and, panicking in fear of the Lord of Death’s henchmen, they will plunge into the river. The streaming acid will"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1," immediately attack all their major and minor body parts and dissolve their bodies, burning their skin and bones. As the acid burns their flesh, their bodies will dissolve into the river like melting lumps of butter. Still, due to the force of their misdeeds, they do not die. Instead, they will now enter a burning forest, which is as dense as a stack of bamboo leaves. Within that forest of continuous flames there is nowhere that a sentient being is not burned and consumed by fire, not even so much as the space of the eye of a needle. Everywhere there are hell beings who yearn for safety and protection as they burn and boil while screaming and running. Until their negative acts have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted they will not have a moment of relief.42:T5ca,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“ ‘How astonishing that since time without beginning their minds have acted as their own deceitful enemy! They lack both ears and hearts, and with minds as hard as stones and diamonds they have constantly been prevented by outer objects from taking any joy in the Dharma. With their craving they never have enough of form, sound, texture, taste, and smell‍—even though those objects are just like poison, weapons, or fire. Thus, the poison of the five objects and the bandits of the six sense sources make them ignorant about the seven branches of awakening and disinclined to traverse the eightfold path of the noble ones. They do not comprehend the nine abodes of sentient beings or the ten virtuous actions. They are fools with respect to the discernment of the eleven grounds. They are skilled in the pursuit of the arising and persistence of the twelve sense sources and in this way pursue what is unskillful. They are ignorant concerning the conduct of the thirteen higher paths. They associate with the fourteen mental perceptions, cannot bear the fifteen harms, and are supported by the sixteen forms of harmful, evil darkness. Their minds are involved in the seventeen childish discernments, the eighteen apertures for the arising of agony, the nineteen paths for the movement of wandering beings, and the twenty hostile abodes.’ Thus, understanding that their minds are fooled in these twenty different ways, the monk will regard sentient beings with compassion."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"43:T47d,“The monk who examines the ripening of the phenomena of karmic action, and who diligently and constantly cuts through the bondage of the māras, will in this way develop wisdom, and so proceed to explore the presence of far more evil realms beyond the Howling Hell. Applying knowledge derived from hearing, he will perceive a realm known as the Hell of Heat. Constructed through a tremendous increase of misdeeds, this hell is ten times more torturous than the great hell of Howling. Its sixteen neighboring realms are as follows: Great Scorching; Resembling White Lotuses; Teeming with Snakes; Swimming Like Fish in Molten Copper; Iron Vase; Flow of Red Rivers; Copious Parasites in Marrow and Bones; Burning Everyone; Infinite Sinking into the Ground; Resembling a Great Lotus; Terrifying Slope; Masses of Vajra-Like Bones; Excruciating Splitting and Cutting by Means of a Black Iron Thread; Terrifying Inferno with Swarms of Crocodiles; Forest Fires Like an Enveloping Darkness; and Tormenting Armor of Vajra-Like Flies. These are the sixteen realms that surround the great Hell of Heat, and the lifespan of the beings there cannot be measured.44:T75a,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“The awful sights and words that one thus perceives will be frightening, for they show that the purchasing power of an infantile being’s accumulated misdeeds is now sufficient to pay for the journey to hell and the karmic ripening of living there. The dying person’s two winds, pippalaka and sūcaka, will now blow fiercely and shake, beat, and smash all the person’s major and minor body parts. As the body is injured, the mind will be tormented by two types of agony that mark the final moments of life. When entering the final moments of life, the minds of those who deceived themselves in life will not focus on the practice of virtue. Consequently, they will experience, “during the intermediate existence, the following omens betokening the sufferings of hell which they themselves have created. Undesirable sounds, textures, tastes, forms, and smells will appear in their perception, and they will hear the voices of the hideous henchmen of the Lord of Death. They will experience winds that are as sharp as razors, burning tastes, terrifying sights that are aggravating to see, and a horrid stench. Frightened by all these objects, the people holding wrong views will perceive the realms of hell, and their perception of hell will be in accordance with the character of their wrong doctrine. At that point the person about to take birth will think, ‘Ah, how delightful is that fine city! I must by all means stay there!’ Hence, they will have their hearts set on going to it. Perceiving the links of existence that are to be experienced, they will thereupon be born there, because as the link of becoming manifests through the condition of grasping, the emergence of that intent will immediately cause birth. Then, as they are born in hell, they must undergo an experience of the combined pains of the Reviving Hell, and so forth, only now intensified tenfold."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"45:T75a,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“The awful sights and words that one thus perceives will be frightening, for they show that the purchasing power of an infantile being’s accumulated misdeeds is now sufficient to pay for the journey to hell and the karmic ripening of living there. The dying person’s two winds, pippalaka and sūcaka, will now blow fiercely and shake, beat, and smash all the person’s major and minor body parts. As the body is injured, the mind will be tormented by two types of agony that mark the final moments of life. When entering the final moments of life, the minds of those who deceived themselves in life will not focus on the practice of virtue. Consequently, they will experience, “during the intermediate existence, the following omens betokening the sufferings of hell which they themselves have created. Undesirable sounds, textures, tastes, forms, and smells will appear in their perception, and they will hear the voices of the hideous henchmen of the Lord of Death. They will experience winds that are as sharp as razors, burning tastes, terrifying sights that are aggravating to see, and a horrid stench. Frightened by all these objects, the people holding wrong views will perceive the realms of hell, and their perception of hell will be in accordance with the character of their wrong doctrine. At that point the person about to take birth will think, ‘Ah, how delightful is that fine city! I must by all means stay there!’ Hence, they will have their hearts set on going to it. Perceiving the links of existence that are to be experienced, they will thereupon be born there, because as the link of becoming manifests through the condition of grasping, the emergence of that intent will immediately cause birth. Then, as they are born in hell, they must undergo an experience of the combined pains of the Reviving Hell, and so forth, only now intensified tenfold."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"46:T75a,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“The awful sights and words that one thus perceives will be frightening, for they show that the purchasing power of an infantile being’s accumulated misdeeds is now sufficient to pay for the journey to hell and the karmic ripening of living there. The dying person’s two winds, pippalaka and sūcaka, will now blow fiercely and shake, beat, and smash all the person’s major and minor body parts. As the body is injured, the mind will be tormented by two types of agony that mark the final moments of life. When entering the final moments of life, the minds of those who deceived themselves in life will not focus on the practice of virtue. Consequently, they will experience, “during the intermediate existence, the following omens betokening the sufferings of hell which they themselves have created. Undesirable sounds, textures, tastes, forms, and smells will appear in their perception, and they will hear the voices of the hideous henchmen of the Lord of Death. They will experience winds that are as sharp as razors, burning tastes, terrifying sights that are aggravating to see, and a horrid stench. Frightened by all these objects, the people holding wrong views will perceive the realms of hell, and their perception of hell will be in accordance with the character of their wrong doctrine. At that point the person about to take birth will think, ‘Ah, how delightful is that fine city! I must by all means stay there!’ Hence, they will have their hearts set on going to it. Perceiving the links of existence that are to be experienced, they will thereupon be born there, because as the link of becoming manifests through the condition of grasping, the emergence of that intent will immediately cause birth. Then, as they are born in hell, they must undergo an experience of the combined pains of the Reviving Hell, and so forth, only now intensified tenfold."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"47:T436,“As the monk who has knowledge of the effects of the ripening of karmic actions continues to examine the regions that surround the Hell of Heat, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and thus perceive a neighboring realm known as Iron Vase. Inquiring into what karmic actions may cause one to be born there, he will see that such a birth is caused by practicing, becoming habituated to, and increasing acts of killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, alcohol consumption, and lying. As for wrong view, some people will kill another person as part of a ritual sacrifice, thinking that this act will grant attainment of the higher realms. Likewise, other people will kill turtles with the goal to master what lies beyond this world, or they may establish others in this belief as well for the rest of their lives. Thus they may cause others to renounce a wholesome path and establish them upon a bad one. Such acts are aspects of wrong view, and when one has separated from one’s body, those acts will cause one to be born in the lower reams, within the hell of Iron Vase.48:T83c,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"In that hell all the torments of the Reviving Hell and so forth are intensified tenfold. This realm contains six vases, each measuring sixty leagues, which bear the following names: Painful Entry, Without Refuge, Constantly Boiled over Fire, Saw-Like Liquid, Garlands of Razors, and Snakes in Boiling Water. The torments of these vases are as indicated by their names. Thus, in the first vase, hell beings are scorched, undergoing all the sufferings of hell. In the second, beings are burned, lacking anything that could protect them. They have no physical refuge, nor do they have any mental refuge, nor any refuge in terms of the Dharma, because those who have ‘taken refuge’ in the lower realms do not find any refuge. In the third vase, one is boiled in molten copper for a long time, until not even a particle of one’s body remains. Then one will be reborn and enter the vase of Saw-Like Liquid. There one will boil in liquid copper, and as one’s body wells up from the bottom to the top, the vase’s saw-like liquid copper will damage and destroy all one’s vital parts. As one later sinks from the top to the bottom, the same destruction will occur. Above, below, and at ground level, one will thus boil like a pea, suffering devastation, destruction, and combustion for a long time. Next, one will enter the Garlands of Razors, a vase full of knives that will cut and cleave the beings of this hell. The torments of the Snakes in Boiling Water involve entering a vase that is half a league tall and full of extremely hot, boiling water. Within the boiling liquid writhe live snakes with the sharpest fangs. Touching or even seeing the fangs will cause a burning sensation and upon touch the fangs pierce through one’s body like razor blades. Such are the snakes that lacerate the beings of this hell. After the hell beings have touched one of these snakes, only their skeletons remain, and the mere sight of the snakes will make them boil and burst like water bubbles. All the while they will be scorched in the boiling water, and so these beings experience excruciatingly fierce torture."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"49:T612,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"“The amassed marrow and bones of the bodies of these hell beings make up a mountain that is five leagues tall and three leagues wide, and within it lurk parasites born of moisture. Those parasites are also a type of sentient being. What type of karmic actions did such parasites perform in the past? When they were men or women, they killed lice, fleas, or bedbugs, or other such creatures, that they found on their own bodies or on the bodies of others. Then, as they separated from their bodies, they fell into the lower realms, and were born as insects in hell. Thus, in accordance with their causal actions, they came to experience life in that mountain, which is known as Source of Bodies. The henchmen of the Lord of Death who are present at Copious Parasites in Marrow and Bones will ignite the with a fire that is produced by karmic action. Thus, those who were fooled by the dung-fed fireplace will burn within Source of Bodies along with all the parasites. As the mountain burns, the flames will be ten leagues tall‍—the beings of this hell are burned along with the parasites by a fire that emerges from their own bodies. The bodies of the parasites at Source of Bodies are small, and consequently their suffering is small. The hell beings, however, are lumped together into an indistinguishable mass, and so their bodies as the garlands of fire surrounding each body burns also other bodies. The beings of this hell are thus burned for innumerable years until finally their negative acts have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"4a:T524,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eIn Buddhist literature, this is an epithet applied to buddhas, most often to Śākyamuni. The Sanskrit term generally means “possessing fortune,” but in specifically Buddhist contexts it implies that a buddha is in possession of six auspicious qualities (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhaga\u003c/em\u003e) associated with complete awakening. The Tibetan term‍—where \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebcom\u003c/em\u003e is said to refer to “subduing” the four māras, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eldan\u003c/em\u003e to “possessing” the great qualities of buddhahood, and \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e’das\u003c/em\u003e to “going beyond” saṃsāra and nirvāṇa‍—possibly reflects the commentarial tradition where the Sanskrit \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagavat\u003c/em\u003e is interpreted, in addition, as “one who destroys the four māras.” This is achieved either by reading \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagavat\u003c/em\u003e as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagnavat\u003c/em\u003e (“one who broke”), or by tracing the word \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhaga\u003c/em\u003e to the root \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√bhañj\u003c/em\u003e (“to break”).\u003c/p\u003e4b:T595,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp\u003eIn the most general sense the devas‍—the term is cognate with the English \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003edivine\u003c/em\u003e‍—are a class of celestial beings who frequently appear in Buddhist texts, often at the head of the assemblies of nonhuman beings who attend and celebrate the teachings of the Buddha Śākyamuni and other buddhas and bodhisattvas. In Buddhist cosmology the devas occupy the highest of the five or six “destinies” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003egati\u003c/em\u003e) of saṃsāra among which beings take rebirth. The devas reside in the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edevalokas\u003c/em\u003e, “heavens” that traditionally number between twenty-six and twenty-eight and are divided between the desire realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekāmadhātu\u003c/em\u003e), form realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003erūpadhātu\u003c/em\u003e), and formless realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eārūpyadhātu\u003c/em\u003e). A being attains rebirth among the devas either through meritorious deeds (in the desire realm) or the attainment of subtle meditative states (in the form and formless realms). While rebirth among the devas is considered favorable, it is ultimately a transitory state from which beings will fall when the conditions that lead to rebirth there are exhausted. Thus, rebirth in the god realms is regarded as a diversion from the spiritual path. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"4c:T532,\u003cp\u003eTuṣita (or sometimes Saṃtuṣita), literally “Joyous” or “Contented,” is one of the six heavens of the desire realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekāmadhātu\u003c/em\u003e). In standard classifications, such as the one in the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e, it is ranked as the fourth of the six counting from below. This god realm is where all future buddhas are said to dwell before taking on their final rebirth prior to awakening. There, the Buddha Śākyamuni lived his preceding life as the bodhisattva Śvetaketu. When departing to take birth in this world, he appointed the bodhisattva Maitreya, who will be the next buddha of this eon, as his Dharma regent in Tuṣita. For an account of the Buddha’s previous life in Tuṣita, see \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Play in Full\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 95), \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"/entity/passage/943039c8-c5ca-4a10-a536-2dd2c725aba6\" title=\"2.12\"\u003e2.12\u003c/a\u003e, and for an account of Maitreya’s birth in Tuṣita and a description of this realm, see \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003e\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"/entity/work/61476bf4-b4db-4e4d-9993-60d347cf1769\" title=\"The Sūtra on Maitreya’s Birth in the Heaven of Joy\"\u003eThe Sūtra on Maitreya’s Birth in the Heaven of Joy\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e, (Toh 199).\u003c/p\u003e4d:T425,\u003cp\u003eThe name of the southern continent in Buddhist cosmology, which can signify either the known human world, or more specifically the Indian subcontinent, literally “the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ejambu\u003c/em\u003e island/continent.” Jambu is the name used for a range of plum-like fruits from trees belonging to the genus \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eSzygium\u003c/em\u003e, particularly \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eSzygium jambos\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003eSzygium cumini\u003c/em\u003e, and it has commonly been rendered “rose apple,” although “black plum” may be a less misleading term. Among various explanations given for the continent being so named, one (in the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e) is that a jambu tree grows in its northern mountains beside Lake Anavatapta, mythically considered the source of the four great rivers of India, and that the continent is therefore named from the tree or the fruit. Jambudvīpa has the Vajrāsana at its center and is the only continent upon which buddhas attain awakening.\u003c/p\u003e4e:T470,\u003cp\u003e“One who belongs to the Kuśika lineage.” An epithet of the god Śakra, also known as Indra, the king of the gods in the Trāyastriṃśa heaven. In the Ṛgveda, Indra is addressed by the epithet Kauśika, with the implication that he is associated with the descendants of the Kuśika lineage (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003egotra\u003c/em\u003e) as their aiding deity. In later epic and Purāṇic texts, we find the story that Indra took birth as Gādhi Kauśika, the son of Kuśika and one of the Vedic poet-seers, after the Puru king Kuśika had performed austerities for one thousand years to obtain a son equal to Indra who could not be killed by others. In the Pāli \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eKusajātaka\u003c/cite\u003e (Jāt V 141–45), the Buddha, in one of his former bodhisattva lives as a Trāyastriṃśa god, takes birth as the future king Kusa upon the request of Indra, who wishes to help the childless king of the Mallas, Okkaka, and his chief queen Sīlavatī. This story is also referred to by Nāgasena in the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eMilindapañha\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e4f:T497,\u003cp\u003eAn ancient Indian kingdom that lay to the south of the Ganges River in what today is the state of Bihar. Magadha was the largest of the sixteen “great states” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emahājanapada\u003c/em\u003e) that flourished between the sixth and third centuries \u003cspan class=\"small-caps\"\u003eʙᴄᴇ\u003c/span\u003e in northern India. During the life of the Buddha Śākyamuni, it was ruled by King Bimbisāra and later by Bimbisāra's son, Ajātaśatru. Its capital was initially Rājagṛha (modern-day Rajgir) but was l"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"ater moved to Pāṭaliputra (modern-day Patna). Over the centuries, with the expansion of the Magadha’s might, it became the capital of the vast Mauryan empire and seat of the great King Aśoka.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThis region is home to many of the most important Buddhist sites, including Bodh Gayā, where the Buddha attained awakening; Vulture Peak (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eGṛdhra­kūṭa\u003c/em\u003e), where the Buddha bestowed many well-known Mahāyāna sūtras; and the Buddhist university of Nālandā that flourished between the fifth and twelfth centuries \u003cspan class=\"small-caps\"\u003eᴄᴇ\u003c/span\u003e, among many others.\u003c/p\u003e50:T462,\u003cp\u003eThe bodhisattva Maitreya is an important figure in many Buddhist traditions, where he is unanimously regarded as the buddha of the future era. He is said to currently reside in the heaven of Tuṣita, as Śākyamuni’s regent, where he awaits the proper time to take his final rebirth and become the fifth buddha in the Fortunate Eon, reestablishing the Dharma in this world after the teachings of the current buddha have disappeared. Within the Mahāyāna sūtras, Maitreya is elevated to the same status as other central bodhisattvas such as Mañjuśrī and Avalokiteśvara, and his name appears frequently in sūtras, either as the Buddha’s interlocutor or as a teacher of the Dharma. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eMaitreya\u003c/em\u003e literally means “Loving One.” He is also known as Ajita, meaning “Invincible.”\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eFor more information on Maitreya, see, for example, the introduction to \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003e\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"/entity/passage/ed4cf305-d6eb-4835-a5cf-7483eb4b4396\" title=\"Maitreya’s Setting Out\"\u003eMaitreya’s Setting Out\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 198).\u003c/p\u003e51:T8d7,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003e(1) A demonic being often bearing the epithet of the “Evil One” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003epāpīyān\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003esdig can\u003c/em\u003e), sometimes said to be the principal deity in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9272\"\u003eHeaven of Making Use of Others’ Emanations\u003c/span\u003e, the highest paradise in the desire realm; also one of the names of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-8531\"\u003egod\u003c/span\u003e of desire, Kāma in the Vedic tradition. He is portrayed as attempting to prevent the Buddha’s enlightenment. In early soteriological religions, the principal deity in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9884\"\u003esaṃsāra\u003c/span\u003e, such as \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9910\"\u003eIndra\u003c/span\u003e, would attempt to prevent anyone’s realization that would lead to such a liberation.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003e(2) The devas ruled over by \u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003eMāra\u003c/span\u003e and assisting his attempts to prevent the Buddha’s enlightenment; they do not wish any being to escape from \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9884\"\u003esaṃsāra\u003c/span\u003e. More generally, they are symbolic of the defects within a person that prevent enlightenment. These four personifications are the \u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003emāra\u003c/span\u003e of the sons of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-8531\"\u003egods\u003c/span\u003e (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edevaputramāra\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003elha’i bu’i bdud\u003c/em\u003e), which is the distraction of pleasures; the \u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003emāra\u003c/span\u003e of death (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emṛtyumāra\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003e’chi bdag gi bdud\u003c/em\u003e); the \u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003emāra\u003c/span\u003e of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9925\"\u003eaggregates\u003c/span\u003e (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eskandhamāra\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ephung po’i bdud\u003c/em\u003e), which is the body; and the \u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003emāra\u003c/span\u003e of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9942\"\u003eafflictions\u003c/span\u003e (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekleśamāra\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003enyon mongs pa’i bdud\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"52:T48a,\u003cp\u003eThose of other religious or philosophical orders, contemporary with the early Buddhist order, including Jains, Jaṭilas, Ājīvikas, and Cārvākas. Tīrthika (“forder”) literally translates as “one belonging to or associated with (possessive suffix \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e–ika\u003c/em\u003e) stairs for landing or for descent into a river,” or “a bathing place,” or “a place of pilgrimage on the banks of sacred streams” (Monier-Williams). The term may have originally referred to temple priests at river crossings or fords where travelers propitiated a deity before crossing. The Sanskrit term seems to have undergone metonymic transfer in referring to those able to ford the turbulent river of saṃsāra (as in the Jain tīrthaṅkaras, “ford makers”), and it came to be used in Buddhist sources to refer to teachers of rival religious traditions. The Sanskrit term is closely rendered by the Tibetan \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emu stegs pa\u003c/em\u003e: “those on the steps (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003estegs pa\u003c/em\u003e) at the edge (\u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003emu\u003c/em\u003e).”\u003c/p\u003e53:T47f,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003e “\u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003ePrātimokṣa\u003c/span\u003e” is the name given to the code of conduct binding on monks and nuns. The term can be used to refer both to the disciplinary rules themselves and to the texts from the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9974\"\u003eVinaya\u003c/span\u003e that contain them. There are multiple recensions of the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003ePrātimokṣa\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e, each transmitted by a different monastic fraternity in ancient and medieval India. Three remain living traditions, one of them the Mūlasarvāstivāda \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9974\"\u003eVinaya\u003c/span\u003e of Tibetan Buddhism. Though the numbers of rules vary across the different recensions, they are all organized according to the same principles and with the same disciplinary categories. It is customary for monastics to recite the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003ePrātimokṣa\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9986\"\u003e Sūtra\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/cite\u003e\u003cspan class=\"ref-pending\" data-href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh2.html\"/\u003e fortnightly. \u003c/p\u003e54:T41a,\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe six practices of the bodhisattva path: generosity (Tib. \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003esbyin pa\u003c/em\u003e; Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edāna\u003c/em\u003e), discipline (Tib. \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003etshul khrims\u003c/em\u003e; Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eśīla\u003c/em\u003e), patience (Tib. \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ebzod pa\u003c/em\u003e; Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekṣānti\u003c/em\u003e), diligence (Tib. \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ebrtson ’grus\u003c/em\u003e; Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003evīrya\u003c/em\u003e), \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-9969\"\u003econcentration\u003c/span\u003e (Tib. \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003ebsam gtan\u003c/em\u003e; Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/em\u003e), and \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-068-021-100012\"\u003einsight\u003c/span\u003e (Tib. \u003cem class=\"foreign text-wy\" lang=\"bo-LATN\"\u003eshes rab\u003c/em\u003e; Skt. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eprajñā\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e55:T50a,\u003cp\u003eOne of the five or six classes of sentient beings, into which beings are born as the karmic fruition of past miserliness. As the term in Sanskrit means “the departed,” they are analogous to the ancestral spirits of Vedic tradition, the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003epitṛ\u003c/em\u003es, who starve without the offerings of descendants. It is also commonly translated as “hungry ghost” or “starving spirit,” as in the Chinese 餓鬼 \u003cem class=\"foreign\"\u003ee gui\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThey are sometimes said to reside in the realm of Yama, but are also frequently described as roaming charnel grounds and other inhospitable or frightening places along with piśācas and other such beings"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,". They are particularly known to suffer from great hunger and thirst and the inability to acquire sustenance. Detailed descriptions of their realm and experience, including a list of the thirty-six classes of pretas, can be found in \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Application of Mindfulness of the Sacred Dharma\u003c/cite\u003e, Toh 287, \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh287.html#UT22084-068-021-1672\" title=\"2.­1281\"\u003e2.­1281\u003c/a\u003e– \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh287.html#UT22084-068-021-1902\" title=\"2.1482\"\u003e2.1482\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e56:T456,\u003cp\u003eA frequently used synonym for \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003ebuddha\u003c/em\u003e. According to different explanations, it can be read as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etathā-gata\u003c/em\u003e, literally meaning “one who has thus gone,” or as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etathā-āgata\u003c/em\u003e, “one who has thus come.” \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eGata\u003c/em\u003e, though literally meaning “gone,” is a past passive participle used to describe a state or condition of existence. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eTatha­(tā)\u003c/em\u003e, often rendered as “suchness” or “thusness,” is the quality or condition of things as they really are, which cannot be conveyed in conceptual, dualistic terms. Therefore, this epithet is interpreted in different ways, but in general it implies one who has departed in the wake of the buddhas of the past, or one who has manifested the supreme awakening dependent on the reality that does not abide in the two extremes of existence and quiescence. It is also often used as a specific epithet of the Buddha Śākyamuni.\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"18:[\"$\",\"$L1f\",null,{\"abbreviations\":[],\"bibliography\":[{\"heading\":\"Bibliography\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"13a7a914-bd19-4f41-b832-b82b0dbf3b8b\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa dam pa’i chos dran pa nye bar gzhag pa\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 287, Degé Kangyur vol. 68 (mdo sde, ya), folios 82a–318a; vol. 69 (mdo sde, ra), folios 1.b–307.a; vol. 70 (mdo sde, la), folios 1.b–312.a; and vol. 71 (mdo sde, sha), folios 1.b–229.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"636e0cbf-9272-4f9c-b0f9-b3d658bb623c\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa dam pa’i chos dran pa nye bar gzhag pa\u003c/em\u003e. bka’ ’gyur (dpe bsdur ma) [Comparative Edition of the Kangyur], krung go’i bod rig pa zhib ’jug ste gnas kyi bka’ bstan dpe sdur khang (The Tibetan Tripitaka Collation Bureau of the China Tibetology Research Center). 108 volumes. Beijing: krung go’i bod rig pa dpe skrun khang (China Tibetology Publishing House), vol. 68, 238–842; vol. 69, 3–828; vol. 70, 3–821; and vol. 71, 3–603.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"36bc5042-9cf7-42bd-b892-cccd0f102dcb\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa dam pa’i chos dran pa nye bar gzhag pa\u003c/em\u003e. Stok Palace Kangyur, vol. 82 (mdo sde, ki), folios 1.b–378; vol. 83 (mdo sde, khi), folios 1.b–370.b; vol. 84 (mdo sde, gi), folios 1.b–383.b; and vol. 85 (mdo sde, ghi), folios 1.b–419.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"412f24b7-4f2f-4e2e-b004-99f584d914b4\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eZhengfa nianchu jing\u003c/em\u003e \u003cem\u003e正法念處經\u003c/em\u003e. In Taishō Tripiṭaka. Edited by Junjirō Takakusu and Kaigyoku Watanabe. Vol. 17, no. 721.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"40b462b0-ae49-454b-aa27-5d026a61f192\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eCabezón, José Ignacio. \u003cem\u003eSexuality in Classical South Asian Buddhism\u003c/em\u003e. Sommerville, MA: Wisdom Publications, 2017.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"c3d99b6d-965c-44c8-ac0c-a921a7243b18\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDemoto, Mitsuyo (2009). “Die 128 Nebenhöllen nach dem Saddharmasmṛ- tyupasthānasūtra.” \u003cem\u003ePāsādikadānam: Festschrift für Bhikkhu Pāsādika\u003c/em\u003e, edited by Martin Straube, Roland Steiner, Jayandra Soni, Michael Hahn, and Mitsuyo Demoto. Marburg: Indica et Tibetica Verlag, 2009: 61–88.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"c46a5e3e-72ce-40aa-b3ee-00f33ea73b40\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDemoto, Mitsuyo, ed. \u003cem\u003eSaddharma­smṛtyupasthāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e: Critical Edition of Ch. 3. Unpublished draft, last modified July 2012. PDF file.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"602990c5-92a3-4fbf-a396-bf44cadc88e3\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDenkarma (\u003cem\u003epho brang stod thang ldan [/ lhan] dkar gyi chos ’gyur ro cog gi dkar chag\u003c/em\u003e). Degé Tengyur, vol. 206 (sna tshogs, jo), folios 294.b–310.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"5983928d-054e-40f9-8672-301a86f760ab\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eHerrmann-Pfandt, Adelheid. \u003cem\u003eDie lHan kar ma: ein früher Katalog der ins Tibetische übersetzten buddhistischen Texte\u003c/em\u003e. Vienna: Verlag der österreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften, 2008. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"3abfca81-e489-48ab-82ea-58d0bf38ad7e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eKritzer, Robert (Forthcoming). “Worms in \u003cem\u003eSaddharma­smṛtyupasthāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e.” In \u003cem\u003eMemorial Volume for Helmut Krasser\u003c/em\u003e. Cambridge: Harvard University Press.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"43c0e73f-e964-42dd-ba08-e0647bba8eea\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eKritzer, Robert (2020). “Meditation on the Body in Chapter 7 of \u003cem\u003eSaddharma­smṛtyupasthāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e.” \u003cem\u003eReligions\u003c/em\u003e 11, no. 6 (2020): 283.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"8ef82ddf-bf4e-4c6c-9e96-71ada3524ba6\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eLin, Li-kuoung, \u0026amp; P. Demiéville. \u003cem\u003eL’aide-mémoire de la vraie loi\u003c/em\u003e. Paris: Adrien-Maisonneuve, 1949. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4942be26-0037-4771-aa26-18995e88ddf7\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eMizuno, Kogen. “On the Ārya-saddharmasmrtyupasthāna-sūtra.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of Indian and Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eIndogaku Bukkyogaku Kenkyu\u003c/em\u003e) 12 (September 1964): 38–47.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"15a6470b-e99a-46dd-b6e5-2447d2d4f42b\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eMoretti, Costantino. “The Thirty-six Categories of ‘Hungry Ghosts’ Described in the Sūtra of the Foundations of Mindfulness of the True Law.” \u003cem\u003eFantômes dans l’Extrême-Orient D’hier et D’aujourd’hui\u003c/em\u003e. Edited by Vincent Durand Dastès, 43–69. Paris: INALCO, 2017.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"6b55a216-a61d-457c-941d-9ca6c468bc98\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eRangjung Dorjé (rang byung rdo rje). \u003cem\u003edam pa’i chos dran pa nye bar bzhag pa’i mdo yi don snang bar byed pa’i bstan bcos\u003c/em\u003e. Lhasa: bod ljongs mi dmangs dpe skrun khang, 2010.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b7b32fa7-fdd5-4036-904e-fc2d9ce2571d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eStuart, Daniel M. (2012). “A Less Traveled Path: Meditation and Textual Practice in the Saddharmasmṛtyupasthāna(sūtra).” PhD diss., University of California, Berkeley.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"85b7245b-3804-413d-a890-bb81c4147bae\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eStuart, Daniel M. (2015a). \u003cem\u003eA Less Traveled Path: Saddharmasmṛtyupasthānasūtra Chapter 2, Critically edited with A Study on Its Structure and Significance for the Development of Buddhist Meditation\u003c/em\u003e. Sanskrit Texts from the Tibetan Autonomous Region (STTAR) 18. Beijing and Vienna: China Tibetology Publishing House and Austrian Academy of Sciences Press, 2015.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"397941dd-74f3-4a0e-b35b-e3b477d332d3\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eStuart, Daniel M. (2015b). “Power in Practice: Cosmic Sovereignty Envisioned in Buddhism’s Middle Period.” \u003cem\u003eThe Critical Review for Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 18 (2015): 165–96.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"eec65810-2844-46e3-8f84-44d99a4723d0\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eStuart, Daniel M. (2017a). “Yogācāra Substrata? Precedent Frames for Yogācāra Thought among Third-Century Yoga Practitioners in Greater Gandhāra.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of Indian Philosophy\u003c/em\u003e 46 (October 2017): 193–240.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"e3276c79-b5b2-4a32-a78c-c81f40c996b8\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eStuart, Daniel M. (2017b). “Unmanifest Perceptions: Mind-Matter Interdependence and Its Consequences in Buddhist Thought and Practice.” In \u003cem\u003eŚrāvakabhūmi and Buddhist Manuscripts\u003c/em\u003e, edited by Jundo Nagashima and Seongcheol Kim, 109–71. Tokyo: Nombre, 2017.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4e5b3f43-c884-4e6a-8a58-33f11aeb8b63\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eStuart, Daniel M. (2019). “\u003ca href=\\\"https://doi.org/10.3390/rel10060363\\\"\u003eBecoming Animal: Karma and the Animal Realm Envisioned through an Early Yogācāra Lens\u003c/a\u003e.” \u003cem\u003eReligions\u003c/em\u003e 10, no. 6 (2019): 363.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"87104957-9eb0-4fdd-af68-c18d0879e793\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003evan der Kuijp, Leonard W. J. “On the Vicissitudes of Subhūticandra’s \u003cem\u003eKāmadhenu\u003c/em\u003e Commentary on the \u003cem\u003eAmarakoṣa\u003c/em\u003e in Tibet.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of the International Association of Tibetan Studies\u003c/em\u003e, no. 5 (December 2009): 1–105.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"effb588f-c504-4587-9d30-cf221156f62e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eWallace, Vesna A., ed. \u003cem\u003eSaddharma­smṛtyupasthāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e: Critical Edition of Ch. 1. Unpublished draft, last modified May 10, 2020. PDF file.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]}],\"endnotes\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6761b636-352c-4397-8ee1-ade869e39603\",\"sort\":88231,\"type\":\"endnotesHeader\",\"label\":\"n.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":5,\"uuid\":\"03b4af22-cb7e-4350-a27c-b28360ca72c0\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Notes\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":5}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6130ae22-fd9a-42bb-b7ea-0062cf779b73\",\"sort\":88233,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.1\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$20\",\"label\":\"i.2\",\"sort\":47,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"5dea2aae-da63-4226-9e9c-bef69e9323d5\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-4\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":85,\"uuid\":\"6130ae22-fd9a-42bb-b7ea-0062cf779b73\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"For a more detailed summary of the contents of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":51}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":56},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"643935d0-63fb-47fc-8abc-2bc1b02a1331\",\"uuid\":\"d52a1850-7503-4e86-b766-8cd6e77767a1\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", see Stuart 2012, pp. 35–69.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":85}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b21f2e9e-9c85-49c4-ad64-a134cc842e77\",\"sort\":88237,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.2\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$21\",\"label\":\"i.3\",\"sort\":68,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"d9c91fea-2c94-48df-813b-843717a7b5ad\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-6\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":90,\"uuid\":\"b21f2e9e-9c85-49c4-ad64-a134cc842e77\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"For an in-depth presentation of this section on mindfulness of the body, see Kritzer 2020.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":90}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"eafd7071-b1dc-4111-96c7-c05487fee160\",\"sort\":88239,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.3\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$22\",\"label\":\"i.3\",\"sort\":68,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"d9c91fea-2c94-48df-813b-843717a7b5ad\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-6\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":151,\"uuid\":\"eafd7071-b1dc-4111-96c7-c05487fee160\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Zhengfa nianchu jing \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"21b8a0c9-8c9c-421f-8972-cd01c7501ee6\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"正法念處經 (Taishō 721). For more information on this version of the sūtra, see Lewis R. Lancaster, “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":117}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"K 801\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":117,\"end\":122},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"link\",\"attrs\":{\"href\":\"http://www.acmuller.net/descriptive_catalogue/files/k0801.html\",\"uuid\":\"7ac4d072-5f10-4237-a8ba-72f669d602c8\",\"type\":\"link\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",” \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":122,\"end\":125}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Korean Buddhist Canon.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":125,\"end\":151},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6ea9ce99-33fd-4f30-81e7-f7c72226e409\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ff3b5861-4efd-4532-9af1-63c088315be2\",\"sort\":88250,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.4\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$23\",\"label\":\"i.3\",\"sort\":68,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"d9c91fea-2c94-48df-813b-843717a7b5ad\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-6\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":103,\"uuid\":\"ff3b5861-4efd-4532-9af1-63c088315be2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Chinese translation was produced by Gautama Prajñāruci, who translated the text from 538 to 541 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":100}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":100,\"end\":102},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":100,\"end\":102,\"uuid\":\"94b88d0c-15e7-42f6-a49d-c0c71381931a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":102,\"end\":103}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6428fb04-6b6e-4bbb-a243-74532f948431\",\"sort\":88256,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.5\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$24\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"sort\":90,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"63d08d5a-8388-403f-8d6f-de0bc7f9c5de\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-9\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":313,\"uuid\":\"6428fb04-6b6e-4bbb-a243-74532f948431\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The AMSD is also the fourth-longest text in the entire Kangyur collection, where only \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":86}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Detailed Explanations of Discipline \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":126},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"88b3f8bb-9c03-4175-85ce-e788af6ba9f7\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(Toh 3, 2217 pages), \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":126,\"end\":147}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in One Hundred Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":147,\"end\":201},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"55696785-292f-4cac-8a05-e06fa38240e8\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":147,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ddff5deb-d134-4439-b9fb-2310c75f1385\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/a66be036-4471-4991-bbb3-29d66f67b70d\",\"entity\":\"a66be036-4471-4991-bbb3-29d66f67b70d\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh8\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":201,\"end\":202},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"55696785-292f-4cac-8a05-e06fa38240e8\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":201,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(Toh 8, 9398 pages), and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":202,\"end\":227}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-five Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":227,\"end\":281},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f3dd3c11-6394-41bb-94fb-57b7592b6e0c\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":227,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d50623b0-3fb5-4d3b-9bbe-8050e38d9f3e\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/ca4f1c8d-b06a-4a3f-b982-014c1f70835f\",\"entity\":\"ca4f1c8d-b06a-4a3f-b982-014c1f70835f\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh9\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":282},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f3dd3c11-6394-41bb-94fb-57b7592b6e0c\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":281,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(Toh 9, 2302 pages) are longer.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":282,\"end\":313}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"209961ce-6d75-4f1a-8a90-44d5e4d80dce\",\"sort\":88265,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.6\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$25\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"sort\":90,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"63d08d5a-8388-403f-8d6f-de0bc7f9c5de\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-9\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":77,\"uuid\":\"209961ce-6d75-4f1a-8a90-44d5e4d80dce\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The partial Sanskrit manuscript does not cover this latter part of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":71}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":76},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"643935d0-63fb-47fc-8abc-2bc1b02a1331\",\"uuid\":\"88e5b923-d093-42dd-9009-c07a1962414e\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":76,\"end\":77}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c91aa30e-2bbd-4477-8871-566659d2d4c7\",\"sort\":88269,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.7\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$26\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"sort\":90,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"63d08d5a-8388-403f-8d6f-de0bc7f9c5de\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-9\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":120,\"uuid\":\"c91aa30e-2bbd-4477-8871-566659d2d4c7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Denkarma, 300.b.4. See also Herrmann-Pfandt 2008, p. 150, n. 271. For further details, see van der Kuijp 2009, pp. 8–13.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":120}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b54d6d7c-b662-4b45-a74c-4acd813b7825\",\"sort\":88272,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.8\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$27\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":157,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"3f815b58-9aaa-4b12-88f0-8c2c9bbe6667\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-14\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23,\"uuid\":\"b54d6d7c-b662-4b45-a74c-4acd813b7825\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stuart 2012, pp. 25–29.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"91edf2bd-a24d-43d6-874f-2dc5db59fe78\",\"sort\":88274,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.9\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$28\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":157,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"3f815b58-9aaa-4b12-88f0-8c2c9bbe6667\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-14\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23,\"uuid\":\"91edf2bd-a24d-43d6-874f-2dc5db59fe78\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stuart 2012, pp. 26–27.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ec751a9e-0c2a-4992-a2e6-cad9c6741fb9\",\"sort\":88276,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.10\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"A critical edition and English translation of the Sanskrit text pertaining to the first part of chapter 2 (according to the Tibetan chapter structure) has been published by Stuart. Critical editions of chapter 1 and the section on the hell realms in the latter part of chapter 2 are currently being prepared by Vesna Wallace and Mitsuyo Demoto, respectively. As we prepared this English translation we consulted Stuart’s critical Sanskrit edition and English translation of that section of the text, which proved to be very beneficial for our translation. Wallace and Demoto also both kindly shared their draft Sanskrit editions with us, which likewise was very helpful for our work. For a detailed discussion of the sūtra’s textual history and the Sanskrit, Chinese, and Tibetan manuscripts, we refer the interested reader to Stuart’s doctoral thesis on the AMSD (2012) and his later published version of his thesis (2015a).\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"sort\":170,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"792d7001-99d4-45f1-ac3e-376729469673\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-15\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":431,\"uuid\":\"ec751a9e-0c2a-4992-a2e6-cad9c6741fb9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"See Stuart 2012 and 2015a. This section corresponds to the whole of chapter 2 according to the Chinese chapter structure. In this English translation we follow the chapter division included in the Tibetan translation, although we have introduced a significant number of headings and subheadings of our own for the sake of readability and ease of navigation. For an overview of the Chinese chapter structure, see Stuart 2012, p. 30.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":431}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a7fe81a5-8ce8-4919-b34d-eb3e7cf832eb\",\"sort\":88278,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.11\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"A critical edition and English translation of the Sanskrit text pertaining to the first part of chapter 2 (according to the Tibetan chapter structure) has been published by Stuart. Critical editions of chapter 1 and the section on the hell realms in the latter part of chapter 2 are currently being prepared by Vesna Wallace and Mitsuyo Demoto, respectively. As we prepared this English translation we consulted Stuart’s critical Sanskrit edition and English translation of that section of the text, which proved to be very beneficial for our translation. Wallace and Demoto also both kindly shared their draft Sanskrit editions with us, which likewise was very helpful for our work. For a detailed discussion of the sūtra’s textual history and the Sanskrit, Chinese, and Tibetan manuscripts, we refer the interested reader to Stuart’s doctoral thesis on the AMSD (2012) and his later published version of his thesis (2015a).\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"sort\":170,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"792d7001-99d4-45f1-ac3e-376729469673\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-15\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":78,\"uuid\":\"a7fe81a5-8ce8-4919-b34d-eb3e7cf832eb\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"These sections correspond to chapter 1 and 3 in the Chinese chapter structure.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":78}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e5a4315a-12ec-4c5b-aa3a-11850275cf9e\",\"sort\":88280,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.12\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$29\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":178,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"93bd509d-754e-44d3-ae64-8eaa672ab29f\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-18\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"e5a4315a-12ec-4c5b-aa3a-11850275cf9e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rangjung Dorjé 2010.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6a779139-3306-466d-9d7d-ae477b5d7544\",\"sort\":88282,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.13\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2a\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":178,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"93bd509d-754e-44d3-ae64-8eaa672ab29f\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-18\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":107,\"uuid\":\"6a779139-3306-466d-9d7d-ae477b5d7544\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"On this topic, see also Kritzer 2020. Other publications on AMSD are found in Mizuno 1964 and Moretti 2017.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":107}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"87f684d3-3484-4c1f-bc75-c2735f0d4d45\",\"sort\":88284,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.14\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2b\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":178,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"93bd509d-754e-44d3-ae64-8eaa672ab29f\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-18\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24,\"uuid\":\"87f684d3-3484-4c1f-bc75-c2735f0d4d45\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Cabezón 2017, pp. 45–65.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9de69797-0c6d-434a-a39d-95b81d540db9\",\"sort\":88286,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.15\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Thus did I hear at one time. While the Blessed One was residing in the brahmin quarter of the village of Nālati near Rājagṛha, venerable Śāradvatīputra one morning went to Rājagṛha together with a great gathering of monks to collect alms. As they were out receiving alms, a large group of the monks came across some wandering non-Buddhist practitioners who were on the way to the same destination, and together they engaged in a Dharma discussion to everyone’s delight and appreciation.\",\"label\":\"p.2\",\"sort\":566,\"type\":\"prologue\",\"uuid\":\"ccd847a8-fdd9-4179-bc5b-2dde849d0669\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-10061\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":681,\"uuid\":\"9de69797-0c6d-434a-a39d-95b81d540db9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mu stegs can spyod pa pa kun tu rgyu ba dag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":49},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":49,\"uuid\":\"fff773c6-1f79-4054-aeed-b1a5831becab\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Here we have taken the phrase (Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":49,\"end\":87}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tīrthika-caraka-parivrājaka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":114},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":114,\"uuid\":\"584dc79d-ba4d-4dc7-aef8-9944e38487d7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") as a generic designation for the same group of people: the flourishing communities of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":114,\"end\":202}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"non-Buddhist\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":202,\"end\":214},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"02f4d334-0e69-4600-a543-0dcea128cf23\",\"uuid\":\"df828d7a-56eb-4ae7-a31f-3565cccbc7b8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":214,\"end\":215}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mendicants\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":215,\"end\":225},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"02bd7ac1-47d5-418a-80ad-998f2aa21c76\",\"uuid\":\"e4dcae5c-53ab-4820-b17e-6393c5a31e30\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" of various religious outlooks, who lived as wandering spiritual seekers (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":225,\"end\":299}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"śramaṇa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":299,\"end\":306},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":299,\"end\":306,\"uuid\":\"8da16201-0843-4a00-b0d6-3d8f418b6f1e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") in India during the time of the Buddha. Often, these wandering practitioners of various religious paths would interact with each other and exchange views and practices, such as we hear in this scripture. Several of the Buddha’s foremost students, such as Śāriputra (a short form of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":306,\"end\":590}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāradvatīputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":590,\"end\":604},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b34f8e95-5fc9-44c9-8e45-f4587adea677\",\"uuid\":\"c5dab2d6-b5a8-4dda-8684-3c464ff72ab2\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), were living the life of a wandering \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":604,\"end\":643}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mendicant\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":643,\"end\":652},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"02bd7ac1-47d5-418a-80ad-998f2aa21c76\",\"uuid\":\"25664f1f-24d9-4ff3-bbd2-0d438ce059b6\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" prior to meeting the Buddha.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":652,\"end\":681}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b4505e92-9c48-448e-9469-6a1fca02b826\",\"sort\":88302,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.16\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2c\",\"label\":\"p.3\",\"sort\":588,\"type\":\"prologue\",\"uuid\":\"b9501750-e955-4e6b-94ad-77339da900d1\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-26\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":40,\"uuid\":\"b4505e92-9c48-448e-9469-6a1fca02b826\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This folio of the Degé Kangyur is blank.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":40}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"dcf53bc6-8404-4a09-abd4-9d099bafcf19\",\"sort\":88304,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.17\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“What is it like to resort to, become habituated to, and increase the misdeed of chatter? Spiritual practitioners who carefully observe inner phenomena will perceive this either through knowledge derived from hearing or by seeing with the divine eye. When resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing chatter, one will end up in the realms of hell beings, animals, or starving spirits. Even if one is born among humans, sharing in their good fortune, one will not be appreciated by others but will be considered unimportant. Whether at the royal palace or in the homes of family and friends, one will be looked at as one gone mad. Such is the misdeed of chatter.\",\"label\":\"1.29\",\"sort\":1118,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"75cdf9dd-5de0-4310-b246-4c7b2f55a6e0\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-64\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":696,\"uuid\":\"dcf53bc6-8404-4a09-abd4-9d099bafcf19\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here “carefully observe inner phenomena” renders the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":61}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nang gi chos la chos kyi rjes su lta ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":61,\"end\":100},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":61,\"end\":100,\"uuid\":\"2b063e9a-3cab-41b3-a4c4-a86c211c4e2c\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Literally, this would read “carefully observe phenomena in terms of inner phenomena.” This expression is repeated multiple times throughout this text and, due to the number of times this phrase is repeated, we have opted to contract the phrase in English so that the translation reads “carefully observe inner phenomena.” Similarly, in the last chapter where the internal and external body are examined, we have rendered “carefully considers and attends to the body in terms of the internal body” as “carefully considers and attends to the internal body.” The same applies to the external body.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":100,\"end\":696}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"93093afa-feaa-4fce-8fce-1fb3fa98b47f\",\"sort\":88308,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.18\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2d\",\"label\":\"1.39\",\"sort\":1260,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"121c2387-949e-4f0d-bb23-eb18c00578df\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-76\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":112,\"uuid\":\"93093afa-feaa-4fce-8fce-1fb3fa98b47f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tib. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":5}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mun nag chen po.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":5,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":5,\"end\":21,\"uuid\":\"d4773a0b-39d7-4918-9960-5ecc6937b219\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" No such name appears below in the description of the hells that surround \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":95}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ultimate Torment\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":95,\"end\":111},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8f5efab1-1d55-410b-b89a-af49ca7d6f7d\",\"uuid\":\"d3cd4ca8-bb85-4cb4-8809-fed580af39a5\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":111,\"end\":112}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3f068d3f-0ed3-4d66-8c0d-3895011deaac\",\"sort\":88314,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.19\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“What does it mean to resort to, become habituated to, and increase acts of sexual misconduct? Overcome by an inappropriate mentality, one may become a type of being with a propensity for desire such as a swallow, duck, pheasant, parrot, peafowl, partridge, fish, or smoky creatures. When such beings die and transfer out of the family of asuras they may be born among humans and associate with bad companions who are full of desire. With them they may then have inappropriate sexual relationships. Being mistaken in these two ways, they are filled with attachment, and they act in inappropriate ways to sate their insatiable desires. This makes it impossible for the gandharvas, otherwise destined to be born there, to take birth, because it desecrates the birthplace. Such are the reasons why sexual misconduct, which is based on improper desire, is a misdeed.\",\"label\":\"1.44\",\"sort\":1314,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ef109669-90c5-4227-9582-308c4a5995ad\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-83\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":46,\"uuid\":\"3f068d3f-0ed3-4d66-8c0d-3895011deaac\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Tib. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"srog chags dud ka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":45},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":45,\"uuid\":\"b031f087-2ea9-465e-8fe4-2564f24ec76d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":46}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"01560d41-985c-465a-bea2-b19654879e16\",\"sort\":88318,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.20\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Those who rattle on like the sound of clapping hands Are inferior among humans. Obtaining that, they do not know the Dharma. They are fooled by those who are deluded.\",\"label\":\"1.62\",\"sort\":1503,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"a6121c71-bf0b-4833-890f-c30749bfe2b3\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-106\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":152,\"uuid\":\"01560d41-985c-465a-bea2-b19654879e16\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"lag pa brdabs pa’i sgra lta bur/ mi ni chung bar gyur pa yin/ gang dag de thob chos mi shes/ mi ni rmongs pa dag gis bslus\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":151},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":151,\"uuid\":\"5458aa15-5938-4445-a459-6339be8a816f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":151,\"end\":152}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"385121d9-44c7-4e96-a22c-9c2187863be3\",\"sort\":88322,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.21\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2e\",\"label\":\"1.75\",\"sort\":1634,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"84998810-13a3-406a-9582-125c548729e0\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-121\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":109,\"uuid\":\"385121d9-44c7-4e96-a22c-9c2187863be3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Based on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sgyu ma\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":20},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"8985ffaa-f9ab-403d-b2d8-9f364b9fb6d4\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" that appears in Choné, Lithang, Narthang, Yongle, and Lhasa. Degé and Stok read \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":20,\"end\":101}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rgyu ma\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":101,\"end\":108},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":101,\"end\":108,\"uuid\":\"095f2bae-7d99-4519-9a72-1f6c383fa5b8\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":108,\"end\":109}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6e0d3746-2a28-4178-9a4c-b8ed8f59cc80\",\"sort\":88328,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.22\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2f\",\"label\":\"1.75\",\"sort\":1634,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"84998810-13a3-406a-9582-125c548729e0\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-121\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":109,\"uuid\":\"6e0d3746-2a28-4178-9a4c-b8ed8f59cc80\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Based on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sgyu ma\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":20},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"4c38e7b4-7809-4040-a32f-975735ef1f1b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" that appears in Choné, Lithang, Narthang, Yongle, and Lhasa. Degé and Stok read \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":20,\"end\":101}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rgyu ma\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":101,\"end\":108},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":101,\"end\":108,\"uuid\":\"b92d8d55-7a12-48bb-a364-53457c01772a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":108,\"end\":109}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"298eabc1-c6ed-41bd-b08c-10c5292ec80f\",\"sort\":88334,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.23\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"(3) “Third, the monarch’s precious bedding is light, smooth, and has upper and lower layers that automatically rearrange themselves in response to the body’s pressure. If the monarch wishes to concentrate, this bedding will free his concentration and brighten his intelligence. If the monarch should become overcome by desire, sitting on this bedding will make him become detached and free from desire. The bedding has the same effect on anger and delusion, and thus the precious bedding is like a seat of meditation. When women see the monarch poised on his precious bedding they will feel the most intense joy yet they will not become excessively desirous. Such are the qualities of the bedding that is the third subsidiary treasure.\",\"label\":\"1.107\",\"sort\":2149,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"f377c5ef-af1d-4a45-8958-1f7abf36c778\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-157\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":103,\"uuid\":\"298eabc1-c6ed-41bd-b08c-10c5292ec80f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation based on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mtho dma’\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":34},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":34,\"uuid\":\"200cf949-cd60-4ae6-89de-637a831cb5ca\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" found in Choné, Lithang, Narthang, and Lhasa. Degé reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":92}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mthon dman\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":102},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":102,\"uuid\":\"2b7ecadb-8858-4000-9de7-3394b7d4f096\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":102,\"end\":103}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4366f6af-25ef-458e-b177-8bf94fbf3917\",\"sort\":88340,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.24\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Furthermore, noble offspring who have given up wrong view will constantly practice, cultivate, and increase that mind of freedom. They will serve spiritual teachers and enjoy listening to the sacred Dharma. With bright minds they will turn toward and prostrate before the Dharma of the buddhas, and their physical and verbal conduct will be peaceful and extremely clear. Thus, when they rest in equipoise with peaceful body, speech, and mind, they are noticed and appreciated by the terrestrial yakṣas. These beings will see that there dwells a noble son, someone inspired by a spiritual teacher, someone free from attachment to the web of the household, someone free from attachment to the objects of the māras‍—an attachment that since beginningless time is created by desire, anger, and delusion, and that accompanies the perceptions of the gods of the desire realm. Thus, the terrestrial yakṣas will notice with great delight that this is a person who is intent on battling the māras and giving up the afflictions.\",\"label\":\"1.117\",\"sort\":2255,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1f9e07b7-1722-40a7-a678-f046dd0e659d\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-168\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":87,\"uuid\":\"4366f6af-25ef-458e-b177-8bf94fbf3917\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Based on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bsten\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"b21b8c27-c8c9-4f4c-bdd7-b060d88cd845\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" that appears in Kangxi, Urga, Narthang, and Lhasa. Degé reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":81}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bstan\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":86},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":86,\"uuid\":\"1e05831e-ddcc-419e-a2be-9699e6630604\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":87}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"975662d1-da5a-4f02-91a0-a83e65625ded\",\"sort\":88346,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.25\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Delighting in solitude, he will develop an inspired mind. With no appreciation for the fun, attractions, and games of the city, he will not look at females in front of him and he has no interest in mundane business. For those who pursue pure conduct, two gatherings are equally to be avoided: business and prostitutes. As he gives up those two, his mind will first become one-pointed, joyous, and buoyant. Thus, he will initially think, ‘How should I first compose and take hold of my mind?’\",\"label\":\"2.3\",\"sort\":2631,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1f3ec1ea-46b0-4bcb-a751-bbe4122cf07b\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-204\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":117,\"uuid\":\"975662d1-da5a-4f02-91a0-a83e65625ded\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Literally “holy life” (Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brahmacārya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":39},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":39,\"uuid\":\"9a33ac0e-e429-4e97-8945-d91c9b43a3f3\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Tib. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":46}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tshang par spyod pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":46,\"end\":65},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":46,\"end\":65,\"uuid\":\"a7dd5559-ccf5-460f-b850-136bfad583a6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). The term refers to a pure and celibate lifestyle.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":65,\"end\":117}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"68833666-52a2-4da2-a2e0-c21653ab7606\",\"sort\":88352,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.26\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$30\",\"label\":\"2.38\",\"sort\":3140,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"5d9c542f-1afb-4448-a81c-c29a5c4e6262\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-241\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":87,\"uuid\":\"68833666-52a2-4da2-a2e0-c21653ab7606\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Following \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":10}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nan gtan\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"1de0acfd-35db-45ac-83a1-c058e1a2930f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in Choné, Lithang, Narthang, Kangxi, and Yongle. Degé reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":79}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"na gtan\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":86},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":86,\"uuid\":\"9bb4775f-9368-4576-9c43-14af80612fd3\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":87}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0f0f2f2b-9a54-481d-8775-de8d882ce7ec\",\"sort\":88358,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.27\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The monk who acknowledges that all of cyclic existence is impermanent will practice the path, become accustomed to it, and increase it. Practicing in this way, he will give up the bonds and the latent tendencies. What are the bonds? They are the bonds of desire, anger, pride, ignorance, view, fixation, doubt, envy, and stinginess. These bonds he will relinquish. What are the latent tendencies? They are the latent tendencies of desirous attachment, desire for existence, view, anger, ignorance, pride, and doubt. Primarily, all these cause one to enter the three realms of existence, to wander on the three grounds, to engage in the three flaws, to adhere to the three times, to cultivate the three sensations that pertain to the three intermediaries, and transmigrate into the three kinds of birth. Thus, they are the causes of cyclic existence.\",\"label\":\"2.63\",\"sort\":3314,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"b8227957-4889-48d2-a88a-c3d1bf62f372\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-267\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":93,\"uuid\":\"0f0f2f2b-9a54-481d-8775-de8d882ce7ec\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bar ma gsum gyi tshor bag sum rjes su bsgoms pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":53},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":53,\"uuid\":\"5b49ce15-175a-468e-b67d-a57327d0922b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":53,\"end\":60}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"trimadhyamās trivedanānubhavitās\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":92},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":92,\"uuid\":\"01bd1191-cacb-4f35-8782-81a5a032adef\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":93}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fa99b852-e8b4-4df6-ab04-42ef9aed07b3\",\"sort\":88364,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.28\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The causes and conditions of all these sensations are not created by perception. Still, without karmic action there will be no craving, and without craving no sensations will occur. As an analogy, in dependence on a wick, a bowl, oil, and fire there can be a moment of candlelight. Such is the way of causes and conditions. Likewise, a monk who sees the causes and conditions of sensation, and who examines and pursues karmic action, understands that all sensations arise by the force of karmic actions. Here the body is the bowl; the faculties are the oil; craving is the wick; desire, anger, and delusion are the fire; and the moment of cognition is the shining candlelight.\",\"label\":\"2.65\",\"sort\":3332,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"907d4e7d-b93d-4eac-8ff8-b2221260771e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-270\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":106,\"uuid\":\"fa99b852-e8b4-4df6-ab04-42ef9aed07b3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“Craving is the wick” inserted based on the Sanskrit (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":54}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vartibhūtā tṛṣṇā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":70},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":70,\"uuid\":\"18d1a5a2-7047-4951-87c4-d8698f9cbb97\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). See Stuart 2012, p. 231 (4.2.22).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":70,\"end\":106}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2ec473b9-817e-4430-b270-a6ff6c66b9ce\",\"sort\":88368,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.29\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“When a monk who observes the sensations of the six objects associated with the body perceives the actual emergence and exhaustion of those sensations, he will enter the fifth ground. Using the lamp of knowing sensations that appear from contact involving the eye, he will ask himself, ‘What are these sensations that are felt and experienced?’\",\"label\":\"2.103\",\"sort\":3655,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"a504834b-36e0-4004-a5e6-760a65c7c996\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-310\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":189,\"uuid\":\"2ec473b9-817e-4430-b270-a6ff6c66b9ce\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Although the text here mentions the fifth \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":42}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ground\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":48},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7ba84e0a-0b64-404d-8d57-0f20cb443c30\",\"uuid\":\"cee2fbb2-0796-4a1a-b512-a12f0253a6a8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", it is unclear where the explanation of the fifth \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":99}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ground\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":105},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7ba84e0a-0b64-404d-8d57-0f20cb443c30\",\"uuid\":\"4650a7a1-e3bd-41ea-b8c5-09abbc8794cd\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" starts, since a similar passage follows below. See also Stuart 2012, p. 327, n. 59.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":189}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0f3ca6ea-e95b-4e1c-9332-c9522f004e1e\",\"sort\":88374,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.30\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“By means of utter disengagement, he will then examine perceptions, noticing that they relate to the perceived marks of eleven different kinds of form. These are long, short, square, circular, triangular, blue, yellow, red, white, and rose red.\",\"label\":\"2.117\",\"sort\":3824,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"79301de3-e767-450c-9cad-d83701b23d25\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-325\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":75,\"uuid\":\"0f3ca6ea-e95b-4e1c-9332-c9522f004e1e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Note that the text only mentions ten kinds. Cf. Stuart 2012, p. 331, n. 70.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":75}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2b32c10b-5813-4f6e-9ce6-1d85809af15f\",\"sort\":88376,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.31\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Animals are consumed by red karmic action, because they prey on one another. They are observed in terms of the perceived marks of fondness for red.\",\"label\":\"2.134\",\"sort\":4018,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3a94832e-8a14-4958-a5d7-ffb2ed436b4e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-343\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":198,\"uuid\":\"2b32c10b-5813-4f6e-9ce6-1d85809af15f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Prior to this sentence the Sanskrit includes a description of the hells and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":76}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"starving spirits\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":76,\"end\":92},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"84f73a9d-4c5c-400b-a557-976d1d6779b3\",\"uuid\":\"e5ab91b5-51ff-40d6-aace-a94876387f42\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as associated with the colors blue and yellow, respectively. See Stuart 2012, p. 335 (5.1.10 and 5.1.11).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":198}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6342380f-b5e2-4691-8475-32e5999d6de5\",\"sort\":88380,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.32\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Those who cause themselves to bleed Remain attached to evil, And disparage the precious saṅgha‍— How could they be thought of as monks?\",\"label\":\"2.151\",\"sort\":4191,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"a6c4b4a5-e499-4471-9a3e-6690d0d98c4b\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-362\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":203,\"uuid\":\"6342380f-b5e2-4691-8475-32e5999d6de5\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bdag nyid gtar bzhag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":49},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":49,\"uuid\":\"dbe82a53-2d2c-4f51-b089-7e723dcbc309\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Based on the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":49,\"end\":73}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bandhakaṃ yadi cātmāṇam kṛtvā papeṣu rajyate\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":73,\"end\":117},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":73,\"end\":117,\"uuid\":\"1f5699c5-75c4-458c-bf4b-fc73f4c93bbf\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Stuart 2012, p. 340, translates: “Making a shackle of the self he delights in evil.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":117,\"end\":203}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4a37ae74-91e4-4bd0-bcbd-64555566e195\",\"sort\":88386,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.33\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$31\",\"label\":\"2.164\",\"sort\":4331,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"57f3fc9a-06ff-4a14-b5fa-ae1c0bcf4032\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-376\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":261,\"uuid\":\"4a37ae74-91e4-4bd0-bcbd-64555566e195\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"chos ’di dag la yid ’jug pa skye ba’i mtshan nyid mi ’dra zhing ngo bo nyid mi ’dra ba yin te/ dper na sa chen po bcu’i chos lta bu’o\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":162},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":162,\"uuid\":\"7e4d1f22-d72b-4cd7-ab0e-2d5449912249\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":162,\"end\":169}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathā daśa mahābhaumā dharmāḥ anyad eve lakṣaṇam cetanāyāḥ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":169,\"end\":227},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":169,\"end\":227,\"uuid\":\"5a57c84d-ce40-4fda-9c02-9b4e4190e471\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Cf. Stuart 2012, p. 343, n. 116.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":227,\"end\":261}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"76b4a3cc-cf6c-484f-b3fd-563ae0f7ad25\",\"sort\":88392,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.34\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Third, as with the imprint of a seal, the emergence of differences is due to all kinds of differences. The first possibility is differences that emerge from differences. The second possibility is the emergence of something that resembles its source, as when a white fabric is produced from white thread. The third option is the emergence of something that conflicts with its source, as when fire emerges from firewood. Fire and wood are in conflict. The fourth option is the emergence of something thick from something thin, as when yogurt emerges from milk. In this way, different objects act as causes and conditions for the eye consciousness and the rest of the consciousnesses to manifest.\",\"label\":\"2.186\",\"sort\":4514,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"da7794c4-326c-4b57-be4a-8990da1df91e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-399\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":68,\"uuid\":\"76b4a3cc-cf6c-484f-b3fd-563ae0f7ad25\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"It is unclear to us what the intended “first” and “second” might be.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":68}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"204cca70-86ef-4a1a-b1de-3b5f02f25641\",\"sort\":88394,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.35\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The first of these alternatives is action without acquisition that harms members of the human class. The second is action with acquisition that harms humans. The third is harmful action both with and without acquisition. The fourth alternative is harmful action that neither involves, nor does not involve, acquisition.\",\"label\":\"2.217\",\"sort\":4775,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"accf4c9a-e14d-489a-bc19-7dbd5611c921\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-432\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":267,\"uuid\":\"204cca70-86ef-4a1a-b1de-3b5f02f25641\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"An action “with \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"acquisition\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":27},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2087a221-01ff-4546-af43-54cc08f2b411\",\"uuid\":\"83bd7900-43cb-4e4e-b1b7-f7ca4f79197c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"” is one that has been “acquired” (Tib. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":67}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"thob pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":74},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"38e56976-6709-4ea0-b6f8-53a6cf0a0368\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":74,\"end\":81}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"prāpta\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":87},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":87,\"uuid\":\"add931dd-6d7c-4bbb-b913-5c04d0739a49\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") within a continuum of the five \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":120}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":130},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b43ca2c1-a3b3-4ed9-b5f9-520b1b5ed114\",\"uuid\":\"a24886cf-38b7-4721-a090-58e564e7a771\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" such that it will ripen its effect within that continuum. In the case of an action without \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":130,\"end\":222}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"acquisition\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":222,\"end\":233},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2087a221-01ff-4546-af43-54cc08f2b411\",\"uuid\":\"6fac91fb-36fb-476b-879e-157eda44da47\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", no such \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":233,\"end\":243}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ripening\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":243,\"end\":251},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e6c5ad9a-9509-4706-9d6f-5fad607030a7\",\"uuid\":\"cf809a76-3851-48dd-a9c3-3426ff1b3a30\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is effectuated.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":251,\"end\":267}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7e2327af-c0ea-47eb-823b-0cab6e70bb2e\",\"sort\":88408,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.36\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“It is perfectly accessible because it is the gateway of gods and humans. This, the perfect gateway of the sacred Dharma, grants deliverance from the city of cyclic existence and access to the transcendence of suffering. As the object of praise of all who train with the genuine view, it is praised by all beings. It is also suitable for kings, because it befits those who master the mind that knows the way to practice the sacred Dharma, or those who pursue that. Thus, the beryl stone and the jewel of the sacred Dharma, with all their perfect qualities, can be seen to have similar traits.\",\"label\":\"2.232\",\"sort\":4911,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"71985d57-af3d-4126-a1cf-0168d9f66f70\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-448\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":195,\"uuid\":\"7e2327af-c0ea-47eb-823b-0cab6e70bb2e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"der zhugs pa zhes bya ba ni\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":33},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":33,\"uuid\":\"6b81798b-6cbf-4b08-b24f-ee79f76948d6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Although the Tibetan text thus appears to join this phrase with the subsequent passage, the translation here follows the Sanskrit edition (Stuart 2015, 480–81).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":195}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f73f1605-534d-4413-851f-f962b2ad3474\",\"sort\":88412,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.37\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Previously, the monk engaged in spiritual practice remained within the three realms of cyclic existence, which is like a five-colored painting. He remained within the desire realm, the form realm, and the formless realm. When the painter-like mind takes desire as its support and reference point, it paints twenty different forms. Moreover, those who are free from desire may observe and attend to the realm of form, and so use the brush of the four concentrations to paint the sixteen different abodes of the realm of form. In the case of those free from the observations of the form realm, the painter-like mind rests in the craving of the four attainments, and so paints the formless realm. Vast is this basis of the three realms.\",\"label\":\"2.242\",\"sort\":5035,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ce319276-608f-4d5a-a1b8-408eb650502f\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-459\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":120,\"uuid\":\"f73f1605-534d-4413-851f-f962b2ad3474\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Based on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bsten\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"b5eebc75-bfc8-44d9-aa04-904284bbaef7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" that appears in Choné, Lithang, Narthang, and Lhasa, and supported by the Sanskrit. Degé reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":114}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bstan\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":114,\"end\":119},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":114,\"end\":119,\"uuid\":\"9971abbd-a4d9-48df-9bb9-a1a56887352b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":119,\"end\":120}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"23c6bd99-9371-4875-8a32-06724a7a9cff\",\"sort\":88418,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.38\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The features of the mind are many, because the five classes of beings have numerous differences in terms of what is observed about them, their essences, and their realms. Those who possess an excellent support have freedoms, endowments, formations that cause rebirth, latent tendencies for a proper attitude, and a constant absence of the triad that includes space. Thus, there are five features. There are boundless differences in terms of the faculties, and the differences with respect to the bases for craving are also numerous. In short, however, the factors of affliction are constituted by the five mental states.\",\"label\":\"2.250\",\"sort\":5135,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"96a50aef-3283-47e4-908b-9755a3ce6b69\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-468\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":161,\"uuid\":\"23c6bd99-9371-4875-8a32-06724a7a9cff\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Presumably the three unconditioned factors‍—analytic cessation, nonanalytic cessation, and space‍—which are characterized by the absence of conditioned entities.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":161}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"de269f04-5cbe-4f42-b1e4-77975a64de13\",\"sort\":88420,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.39\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$32\",\"label\":\"2.263\",\"sort\":5249,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"050de3d4-b225-4810-acee-9efbd5690745\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-482\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":182,\"uuid\":\"de269f04-5cbe-4f42-b1e4-77975a64de13\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Although all the Tibetan editions consistently read \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":52}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dga’\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":56},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":56,\"uuid\":\"4219a17b-8676-4366-a9c8-81c6886468b6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the translation here assumes \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":87}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dka’\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":91},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":91,\"uuid\":\"24887c7b-0b48-4774-a109-bdf5131ae6a7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in accord with the Sanskrit edition and the wording in the previous sentence (F.144.a1–2).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":91,\"end\":182}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d9513445-0f09-427c-b66e-cd1b29121ad0\",\"sort\":88426,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.40\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“How does karmic action bring pleasant ripening despite the present ripening not being pleasant? The cognition of forms that are perceived by means of the eyes entails visual contact. When at that point the mind is directed correctly, so that it becomes disengaged and unattached, the present ripening may be painful, yet it will transform and so lead to the joys of gods and humans as well as the perfection of the transcendence of suffering. The same holds true for the consciousness of the ears, nose, tongue, body, and mind.\",\"label\":\"2.269\",\"sort\":5343,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"e3e2843f-6bcf-4bd4-829a-ec24d61339d9\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-489\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":140,\"uuid\":\"d9513445-0f09-427c-b66e-cd1b29121ad0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Tibetan text appears to have a negation too many here: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":59}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bde ba ma yin pa ma yin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":82},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":82,\"uuid\":\"a8a1da69-4dd8-41a7-b53a-4d102dc466a7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". This is supported by the Sanskrit (Stuart 2015, p. 524).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":82,\"end\":140}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a5899160-b21e-439c-aeeb-cdf5f5a0e010\",\"sort\":88430,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.41\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Wondering what karmic actions lead to birth in the region known as the Swamp of Filth, the monk may investigate things by means of knowledge derived from hearing or through the divine eye. Thus he will see that similarly unconfessed, duly prepared, completed, and accumulated acts of killing that are driven by desire‍—as when one hunts birds using birds, lets bears kill bears, or eagles kill eagles, traps deer in snares or hunts them‍—constitute the generative unvirtuous actions that lead to birth in the Swamp of Filth.\",\"label\":\"2.301\",\"sort\":5753,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7c3f5220-999a-45c6-8089-5c5b72bf18ba\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-525\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"a5899160-b21e-439c-aeeb-cdf5f5a0e010\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The text could be implying bear fights and eagle fights staged for entertainment.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"110485af-22d9-415a-afaa-a179c266d845\",\"sort\":88432,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.42\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Some of the harms of that realm are as follows. The Swamp of Filth is filled with filth, putrid corpses, and worms with diamond-hard mouths. If one happens to swallow any of the filth there, the worms within the filth will enter one’s body and begin to consume it. They will begin by eating one’s lips, and continue with the tongue, palate, throat, heart, liver, spleen, vital points, pakṣālikā, entrails, colon, and stomach. From there the worms will spread throughout the impure body, consuming one’s teeth, flesh, and lungs. Thus, one will experience burning, fierce, and excruciating sensations for many hundreds of thousands of human years. Corresponding with the evil that was done, one will be killed by birds if one took the lives of birds, by bears if in previous times one killed bears, and by other wild animals if one trapped, ensnared, hunted, or preyed on such animals before. As the effects of one’s actions ripen, the worms will enter one’s body and consume it, just as before one would eat the animals.\",\"label\":\"2.302\",\"sort\":5765,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"92dbcdba-d3a2-4639-a31e-1a3dfca1b663\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-527\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":49,\"uuid\":\"110485af-22d9-415a-afaa-a179c266d845\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"We have not been able to identify this body part.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":49}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"78cec28e-4a27-4640-b0b2-d54ca57184c4\",\"sort\":88434,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.43\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Some of the harms of that realm are as follows. The Swamp of Filth is filled with filth, putrid corpses, and worms with diamond-hard mouths. If one happens to swallow any of the filth there, the worms within the filth will enter one’s body and begin to consume it. They will begin by eating one’s lips, and continue with the tongue, palate, throat, heart, liver, spleen, vital points, pakṣālikā, entrails, colon, and stomach. From there the worms will spread throughout the impure body, consuming one’s teeth, flesh, and lungs. Thus, one will experience burning, fierce, and excruciating sensations for many hundreds of thousands of human years. Corresponding with the evil that was done, one will be killed by birds if one took the lives of birds, by bears if in previous times one killed bears, and by other wild animals if one trapped, ensnared, hunted, or preyed on such animals before. As the effects of one’s actions ripen, the worms will enter one’s body and consume it, just as before one would eat the animals.\",\"label\":\"2.302\",\"sort\":5765,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"92dbcdba-d3a2-4639-a31e-1a3dfca1b663\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-527\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":260,\"uuid\":\"78cec28e-4a27-4640-b0b2-d54ca57184c4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ji tsam du sdig pa bya’i srog gcod pa ni byas gsod/ srog chags dud ka lta bu ni dud ka lta bus gsod/ rgya dang gdos kyis ri dags gsod pa rngon pa spyod pa’i ngang tshul can ni de dag gis gsod cing / de gis dbang du byas nas za ste\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":259},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":259,\"uuid\":\"dcfdbe7e-d033-4a9d-82a2-950dda054ced\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":259,\"end\":260}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a367b53c-0576-41bb-9dcd-6cb0da60bfd8\",\"sort\":88438,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.44\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The monk will then consider the karmic ripening that produces Boiling Cauldrons, the third realm that neighbors the Reviving Hell. Wondering what types of actions may bring birth there, he will examine things with knowledge derived from hearing. He will then understand that by flaying, boiling, and cooking camels, pigs, rabbits, and other such animals, one will upon separating from one’s body fall into a realm of misery where, in accordance with one’s karmic seeds, one will be boiled in a cauldron. Thus, thrown into an iron cauldron that is kept boiling by intense fire for many hundreds of thousands of years one will endure torture there.\",\"label\":\"2.308\",\"sort\":5831,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"74dc4c91-d6ab-450c-b98f-6b62ebf5e040\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-535\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":179,\"uuid\":\"a367b53c-0576-41bb-9dcd-6cb0da60bfd8\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The text also mentions three other animals, whose names are listed in Sanskrit transcription: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":94}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"*mātalaka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":103},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":103,\"uuid\":\"36a57d3a-f543-43e3-ab24-33e13303dcbe\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":103,\"end\":105}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"*mātolaka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":114},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":114,\"uuid\":\"9494f6c8-399f-427c-8f77-70d3d77b1530\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":114,\"end\":120}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"*dṛśyabhute\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":131},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":131,\"uuid\":\"bb721f9a-20ba-4040-bbc9-9632fbec60a6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". We have been unable to identify these animals.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":131,\"end\":179}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5ac754c4-29eb-45ea-bd90-9985541b2a44\",\"sort\":88450,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.45\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$33\",\"label\":\"2.311\",\"sort\":5859,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"764228e7-cdef-446d-b1da-bbf961dfba2e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-539\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":188,\"uuid\":\"5ac754c4-29eb-45ea-bd90-9985541b2a44\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The following description of the human conditions that resemble the sufferings in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":86}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Reviving Hell\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":99},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"686b99cb-08b7-4221-bf62-e71f4c13780e\",\"uuid\":\"804db43b-d844-47f3-b49c-01876fa42ead\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is at times unclear to us and the translation should therefore be regarded as tentative.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":188}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2dd9a69f-1182-4a32-9022-e859ad2de973\",\"sort\":88454,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.46\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$34\",\"label\":\"2.311\",\"sort\":5859,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"764228e7-cdef-446d-b1da-bbf961dfba2e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-539\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":176,\"uuid\":\"2dd9a69f-1182-4a32-9022-e859ad2de973\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Tibetan here mentions another torturous sensation: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"lum pa ka’i tshor ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":75},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":75,\"uuid\":\"e8b08f1d-1730-44f8-a650-3197e95be0a5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":75,\"end\":77}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"lum pa ka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":77,\"end\":86},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":77,\"end\":86,\"uuid\":\"1af96cfb-4342-43e2-a2ba-589592c6e910\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" may be a Sanskrit transliteration, but we have not been able to find any comparable term.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":176}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3b185818-371b-4895-8a82-7db7bd658f23\",\"sort\":88460,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.47\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$35\",\"label\":\"2.311\",\"sort\":5859,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"764228e7-cdef-446d-b1da-bbf961dfba2e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-539\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"3b185818-371b-4895-8a82-7db7bd658f23\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7debbe59-2af4-41ff-9cc7-2d55e3fd805b\",\"sort\":88462,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.48\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$36\",\"label\":\"2.311\",\"sort\":5859,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"764228e7-cdef-446d-b1da-bbf961dfba2e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-539\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":52,\"uuid\":\"7debbe59-2af4-41ff-9cc7-2d55e3fd805b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sa’i tshor ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":19},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":19,\"uuid\":\"9ae48fc0-450f-4f12-a905-378a2abee7ce\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The meaning is not clear to us.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":19,\"end\":52}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1aedcc52-9935-44b0-bcb1-d355eaea26e0\",\"sort\":88466,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.49\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$37\",\"label\":\"2.311\",\"sort\":5859,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"764228e7-cdef-446d-b1da-bbf961dfba2e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-539\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":27,\"uuid\":\"1aedcc52-9935-44b0-bcb1-d355eaea26e0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Not translated: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"khar gongs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":26},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":26,\"uuid\":\"8f7598c9-d528-43ee-9d14-764420bd4190\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":27}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bf6941c2-bf2a-470a-9d3f-77920807e386\",\"sort\":88470,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.50\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$38\",\"label\":\"2.311\",\"sort\":5859,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"764228e7-cdef-446d-b1da-bbf961dfba2e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-539\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":151,\"uuid\":\"bf6941c2-bf2a-470a-9d3f-77920807e386\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The animal is listed in the text as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":36}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"*marakoṭaka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":36,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":36,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"de6554a0-8271-4219-98e2-f244a69568f2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (unidentified). Here and below we have translated this animal as “biting insects,” or simply “insects.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":151}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e3dced4e-85d9-4d9e-8efd-3ca5cbc03d1c\",\"sort\":88478,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.51\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$39\",\"label\":\"2.311\",\"sort\":5859,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"764228e7-cdef-446d-b1da-bbf961dfba2e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-539\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":116,\"uuid\":\"e3dced4e-85d9-4d9e-8efd-3ca5cbc03d1c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The text here also features a seemingly Sanskrit transcription, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":64}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"*cālbīnaka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":64,\"end\":74},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":64,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"7d4f5398-443e-436d-af79-2f917f54d115\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which we have not been able to identify.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":74,\"end\":116}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"db62814b-2f38-4090-a84d-f34ddd762a44\",\"sort\":88482,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.52\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$3a\",\"label\":\"2.311\",\"sort\":5859,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"764228e7-cdef-446d-b1da-bbf961dfba2e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-539\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":80,\"uuid\":\"db62814b-2f38-4090-a84d-f34ddd762a44\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation uncertain. The Tibetan reads: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":42}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rgya mtsho sum cu’i dbu ba’i tshor ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":79},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":79,\"uuid\":\"1841ba54-7f9a-4849-8694-99bdeee342c3\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":80}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"de1340cc-d2b4-4b6c-ad54-3d7f5c409001\",\"sort\":88486,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.53\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The painter of the mind thus draws its designs with the brush of desire and the paint of unvirtuous thoughts upon the canvas of the heart. Thus, the restrictive marks of having children and a wife will come to be experienced. One will not be defeated by one’s own positive karmic actions, but for as long as one has not overcome, relinquished, and exhausted one’s negative actions, one will not die.\",\"label\":\"2.312\",\"sort\":5893,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1d58a92a-c6c1-41b2-a55e-274a1cf05c6c\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-548\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43,\"uuid\":\"de1340cc-d2b4-4b6c-ad54-3d7f5c409001\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"snod kyi gzhi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":42,\"uuid\":\"1e94ebd8-d77d-40a7-b4b8-830b1f460b37\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":43}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1e9c6467-f37d-4696-bff7-7b223e306ebd\",\"sort\":88490,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.54\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The painter of the mind thus draws its designs with the brush of desire and the paint of unvirtuous thoughts upon the canvas of the heart. Thus, the restrictive marks of having children and a wife will come to be experienced. One will not be defeated by one’s own positive karmic actions, but for as long as one has not overcome, relinquished, and exhausted one’s negative actions, one will not die.\",\"label\":\"2.312\",\"sort\":5893,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1d58a92a-c6c1-41b2-a55e-274a1cf05c6c\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-548\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"1e9c6467-f37d-4696-bff7-7b223e306ebd\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0e830869-0ca1-4763-ac05-0c631018cc50\",\"sort\":88492,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.55\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“At this point, there are some verses: “When one remains within the home of craving, The fish-like mind is bewildered. Hence, when a deed is carried out there is happiness, Yet when the outcome is experienced there will be lamentation.\",\"label\":\"2.319\",\"sort\":5959,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1b524327-79bc-4e2a-800a-f5fbadc44f77\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-557\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":84,\"uuid\":\"0e830869-0ca1-4763-ac05-0c631018cc50\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The following passage, apart from the first verse, is in prose in the Sanskrit text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":84}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c3bd7d57-60f2-4ec7-972b-4564f7f8b904\",\"sort\":88494,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.56\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“That hell features numerous tortures. Bound by a burning rope, one may be pulled up vertically only to be dropped into the abyss from a distance of many leagues. Likewise, as soon as one is born there, one will be made to walk on razors and sharp weapons. With all one’s major and minor body parts in pain. Deceived by one’s own mind, one will roam through cyclic existence, lost in darkness due to delusion. One’s body, which is burning like a forest fire, will be devoured by dogs with extremely sharp fangs. Those who live in that hell have no protector, no guardian, no benefactor, and no one to comfort them.\",\"label\":\"2.327\",\"sort\":6041,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"f2b4462f-8017-4ff9-82ba-a61e0c4ac294\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-568\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":105,\"uuid\":\"c3bd7d57-60f2-4ec7-972b-4564f7f8b904\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In place of “sharp,” the Skt. reads “glistening” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":50}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"pradīpta\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":58},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":58,\"uuid\":\"1a51a57f-e2a3-4a5b-b13f-d2eca2b4c9f2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). The Sanskrit word could also mean “burning.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":105}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"23ab6162-a5fc-45e5-bda3-6ee68d042a7f\",\"sort\":88498,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.57\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$3b\",\"label\":\"2.348\",\"sort\":6238,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"25586e3d-2cda-49df-8709-35a10461501b\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-592\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28,\"uuid\":\"23ab6162-a5fc-45e5-bda3-6ee68d042a7f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"lha la snyad btags pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":27},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":27,\"uuid\":\"2b91b37e-cddf-4e17-8500-7910efaf7de0\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":28}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"396ee67b-4111-4fb1-ae05-854af4d5024e\",\"sort\":88502,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.58\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Those who neither approach The transcendence of suffering nor the realms of the gods Are highly deluded about causal powers. Theirs is the blackest of all forms of darkness.\",\"label\":\"2.358\",\"sort\":6332,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"8cf1ee60-5c37-41d6-b33b-86949e6763f1\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-604\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":78,\"uuid\":\"396ee67b-4111-4fb1-ae05-854af4d5024e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The remainder of the versified part is rendered in prose in the Sanskrit text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":78}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b42ce7bf-cdf4-4692-bf97-39b5a73c197d\",\"sort\":88504,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.59\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“One will then become a herder of camels, Pack oxen, mares, elephants, or horses, Or a hunter who sets traps. Impoverished, one’s life will be short.\",\"label\":\"2.363\",\"sort\":6383,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c5c86bd2-ec43-4e40-ad3e-4bd2e2149ac4\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-610\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43,\"uuid\":\"b42ce7bf-cdf4-4692-bf97-39b5a73c197d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This line is absent from the Sanskrit text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2c2eae02-bba3-4b73-a16f-5b6f452e9fe9\",\"sort\":88506,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.60\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The monk who examines the regions surrounding the Black Line Hell will at this point stop his inquiry without concerning himself with any other neighboring realms. The great Black Line Hell with its sixteen surrounding realms is similar to the great Reviving Hell with its sixteen surrounding realms. As the monk examines the neighboring reaches of this second hell, he will comprehend the ripening of the phenomena of karmic action. Understanding the essential character of the matured results of flawed action, he will see that some acts are done and accumulated, others are accumulated but not engaged in, and still others are done but not accumulated. Acts that were done and accumulated are certain to ripen whereas acts that were accumulated but not carried out and acts that were carried out but not accumulated do not have any certain ripening.\",\"label\":\"2.365\",\"sort\":6403,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"392a0fbf-f300-4333-8d76-148b4782da99\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-613\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":217,\"uuid\":\"2c2eae02-bba3-4b73-a16f-5b6f452e9fe9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Full karmic \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":12}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ripening\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":20},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e6c5ad9a-9509-4706-9d6f-5fad607030a7\",\"uuid\":\"98f720c7-5c70-4e6e-a10b-a74e02734728\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" results from acts that are carried out as well as accumulated. Karmic accumulation generally requires that the given act is intentional, seen through to completion, and not subsequently regretted.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":20,\"end\":217}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e1178335-4bf9-48eb-a43c-922d9b8e80c4\",\"sort\":88510,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.61\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$3c\",\"label\":\"2.372\",\"sort\":6498,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"98b3bc04-2d50-4ab6-97e5-297fc2c06c7a\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-622\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17,\"uuid\":\"e1178335-4bf9-48eb-a43c-922d9b8e80c4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"thags star\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":16},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"94483c60-2260-4bc3-b19f-b7c68d2ce73b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":17}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2af4933a-db36-46df-9976-5ce7a5f91a38\",\"sort\":88514,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.62\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$3d\",\"label\":\"2.379\",\"sort\":6556,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"a18d4593-63a5-40ef-b1c6-f5e0fa9b79f6\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-630\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":96,\"uuid\":\"2af4933a-db36-46df-9976-5ce7a5f91a38\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit includes here several lines of additional text that sum up the last few paragraphs.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":96}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"019da07e-6e48-491d-b1f9-dc6704968df0\",\"sort\":88516,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.63\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“In the land of humans you may not Have caused yourselves to suffer, But in your final human existence You engaged in evil for your children’s sake.\",\"label\":\"2.382\",\"sort\":6588,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"149f652f-8f46-4414-af17-df0376fbde71\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-635\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":153,\"uuid\":\"019da07e-6e48-491d-b1f9-dc6704968df0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mi yi tha ma bu yi don/ /des na sdig pa khyod kyis byas/ /gang gis sngan byas sdig byas pa/ /phyis ni gnod par mi ’gyur min\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":152},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":152,\"uuid\":\"e80bf1f9-a733-4a3e-9a94-b2deb185ac58\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":152,\"end\":153}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"34e3c9e7-ae1f-486d-8ece-a2fc81dc6e9a\",\"sort\":88520,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.64\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The monk who has knowledge of the ripening of karmic effects will further examine the neighboring regions of the great Crushing Hell. Thus he will notice sixteen realms that surround it: Infinite Torture, Slicing Like a Bottle-Gourd Fruit, Ripping of All Vital Points, the Lump, Terrifying Sight, Copious Degeneration, Unbearable Harm, Crier, Wailer, Pleading, Fire that Brings Forth a Torrent of Tears, Cessation of All Faculties, Endless Agony, Bursting Like Lotuses, Bursting Like Great Lotuses, Furnace, and Metallic Fire.\",\"label\":\"2.390\",\"sort\":6658,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"03d6d6f9-de6a-485c-99d7-e5fb4247229a\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-644\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":449,\"uuid\":\"34e3c9e7-ae1f-486d-8ece-a2fc81dc6e9a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The names “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":11}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Lump\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":11,\"end\":15},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"3d3649dd-8aa0-47cd-a66e-f5af7b1e1fb0\",\"uuid\":\"de86eb2d-6c67-4e04-acba-a57148b36b29\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",” “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":15,\"end\":19}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Copious Degeneration\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":19,\"end\":39},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"761850dc-1d10-476f-8b06-f12e2780c010\",\"uuid\":\"1de04db9-8009-48c5-8a9a-f277c488df6e\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",” and “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":47}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Crier\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":52},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"298ea33b-ef8e-43a2-9e7d-99f27a405232\",\"uuid\":\"85bd9f62-9697-459f-9729-7be715a9e5fc\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",” could not be meaningfully matched with the Sanskrit names; possibly they are meant to correspond with the “Hell of Lumps” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":178}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"piṇḍo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":178,\"end\":183},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":178,\"end\":183,\"uuid\":\"4008e604-ad1e-420d-ba61-28c576c80881\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" [sic]\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":183,\"end\":189}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"naraka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":189,\"end\":195},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":189,\"end\":195,\"uuid\":\"e6bbab05-432d-4975-8627-201d476e9d2d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"‍—the sense is unclear), and the “Heavy Punishment” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":195,\"end\":248}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yātanabahula\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":248,\"end\":260},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":248,\"end\":260,\"uuid\":\"0578c4f2-ee09-4d56-ad39-7ba1ce7b66e7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), and the Cuṭucuṭu (the meaning is unclear). The hell called “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":260,\"end\":323}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Pleading\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":323,\"end\":331},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7a74624f-e5ae-4c30-b282-1bf2d12fe822\",\"uuid\":\"7707de78-fceb-437d-a21b-b2acb3b58480\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"” which is included in this list of hells and increases its number to seventeen, doesn’t appear mentioned again below.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":331,\"end\":449}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"69520e35-2acd-4283-a32a-1ac873f9b2b6\",\"sort\":88536,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.65\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk further examines the regions surrounding the great Crushing Hell, he will perceive the hell realm known as Terrifying Sight. Wondering what karmic actions may cause beings to take birth there, he will understand that such a birth is due to becoming habituated to and increasing acts of killing, taking what was not given, and sexual misconduct in such a way that they are undertaken and accumulated. As for killing and stealing, it is just as in the previous cases. However, in terms of sexual misconduct, the specific aspect is that of having forcefully placed one’s mouth onto a child’s genitals. When one later separates from one’s body, one will suffer a downfall into the lower realms, taking birth in the hell of Terrifying Sight.\",\"label\":\"2.396\",\"sort\":6783,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1ce6ae6c-3633-4705-9d5d-01fedfca43a0\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-651\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":203,\"uuid\":\"69520e35-2acd-4283-a32a-1ac873f9b2b6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gang gis byis pa gzhan du bzhin du mthus sba ba’i gnas su bcug pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":94},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":94,\"uuid\":\"3c2513b3-f404-4f7c-a629-be424b146da6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Sanskrit reads, “forcing the children of others, while they weep and cry, to stimulate one’s own genitals.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":203}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"540d20c1-66c8-4cfc-a617-6c771e435668\",\"sort\":88540,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.66\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The monk has now become aware of the nature of the karmic effects that manifest as the neighboring regions of three great hells. As he apprehends, views, and observes such ripening of karmic effects, he develops renunciation with respect to existence, and without wishing for any of the objects of the māras, he will engage in spiritual practice and observe inner phenomena. When the terrestrial yakṣas notice the monk’s endeavors, they will inform the celestial yakṣas, who will in turn pass the news on to the Four Great Kings. Thus, in the same way as before, the news will finally reach the Heaven of Limitless Light and the gods there will learn that, ‘In Jambudvīpa the noble son known as so-and-so, who is of such and such a town, has shaved off his hair and beard, donned the saffron-colored robes, and with faith gone forth from the household to become a homeless mendicant. Now he has entered the ninth ground.’\",\"label\":\"2.450\",\"sort\":7399,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c8f71cef-ac30-4e11-9f3f-c07748a087e6\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-707\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":61,\"uuid\":\"540d20c1-66c8-4cfc-a617-6c771e435668\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Note that this section otherwise belongs to the tenth \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":54}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ground\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":60},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7ba84e0a-0b64-404d-8d57-0f20cb443c30\",\"uuid\":\"9894b6af-f619-48a2-a9f6-22e61852c521\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":61}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"15b5befd-dc1e-4640-83f1-dc76a2fc5e95\",\"sort\":88544,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.67\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk who has knowledge of the ripening of karmic effects examines the regions that surround the Great Howling Hell he will notice sixteen realms that neighbor it: Scream, Screams Everywhere, Burning Hair, Sparks and Parasites, Flaming Iron Club, Rain of Burning Stones, Impossible to Die, Iron Wilderness, Veil of Complete Darkness, Borderlands of the Lord of Death, Śālmali Forest, Great Śālmali Forest, Smoky Forest of Burning Plantains, Smoky Forest of Burning Embers, Forest of Fiery Mist, and Worrisome. These are the sixteen neighboring realms of the Great Howling Hell.\",\"label\":\"2.482\",\"sort\":7683,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"353937a4-05b0-4aa0-8bae-24173ece59f3\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-741\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":112,\"uuid\":\"15b5befd-dc1e-4640-83f1-dc76a2fc5e95\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The text only lists fifteen such hells. See, however, our \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":58}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.69 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":63},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"699536b8-8570-4f00-b6d3-32626f69e95c\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/713955e9-48bb-46d9-a097-af5f37a9f72b\",\"entity\":\"713955e9-48bb-46d9-a097-af5f37a9f72b\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"below regarding the hell of the “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":96}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śālmali Forest\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":96,\"end\":110},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"0c9aad12-4844-4711-b448-a7d0d2a420cb\",\"uuid\":\"22cc714e-f27a-4d4d-b1d2-11f8921e0f1d\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":110,\"end\":112}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"13e14e60-ce17-4e6c-af79-3d74e2c13978\",\"sort\":88550,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.68\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk who has knowledge of the ripening of karmic effects examines the regions that surround the Great Howling Hell he will notice sixteen realms that neighbor it: Scream, Screams Everywhere, Burning Hair, Sparks and Parasites, Flaming Iron Club, Rain of Burning Stones, Impossible to Die, Iron Wilderness, Veil of Complete Darkness, Borderlands of the Lord of Death, Śālmali Forest, Great Śālmali Forest, Smoky Forest of Burning Plantains, Smoky Forest of Burning Embers, Forest of Fiery Mist, and Worrisome. These are the sixteen neighboring realms of the Great Howling Hell.\",\"label\":\"2.482\",\"sort\":7683,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"353937a4-05b0-4aa0-8bae-24173ece59f3\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-741\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":102,\"uuid\":\"13e14e60-ce17-4e6c-af79-3d74e2c13978\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gsod med\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":14},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":14,\"uuid\":\"2e9b0852-2030-4891-af56-d1fae5441dca\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". In the description of this hell found below, it is called “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":14,\"end\":75}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"No Death\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":75,\"end\":83},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7b73bb25-bce3-47c5-b8e2-9d0c8f89ef4f\",\"uuid\":\"b616a322-d6ba-4f25-8565-0829e2b53609\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"” (Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":92}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’chi med\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":100},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":100,\"uuid\":\"65492bcf-cec7-465b-8281-de9c297f65b9\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":100,\"end\":102}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"713955e9-48bb-46d9-a097-af5f37a9f72b\",\"sort\":88558,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.69\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk who has knowledge of the ripening of karmic effects examines the regions that surround the Great Howling Hell he will notice sixteen realms that neighbor it: Scream, Screams Everywhere, Burning Hair, Sparks and Parasites, Flaming Iron Club, Rain of Burning Stones, Impossible to Die, Iron Wilderness, Veil of Complete Darkness, Borderlands of the Lord of Death, Śālmali Forest, Great Śālmali Forest, Smoky Forest of Burning Plantains, Smoky Forest of Burning Embers, Forest of Fiery Mist, and Worrisome. These are the sixteen neighboring realms of the Great Howling Hell.\",\"label\":\"2.482\",\"sort\":7683,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"353937a4-05b0-4aa0-8bae-24173ece59f3\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-741\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":215,\"uuid\":\"713955e9-48bb-46d9-a097-af5f37a9f72b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śālmali Forest\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1,\"end\":15},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"0c9aad12-4844-4711-b448-a7d0d2a420cb\",\"uuid\":\"53063244-e733-4f49-8672-0c78804f8761\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"” is absent from the list in both the Tibetan and the Sanskrit, but its description is included later on as one of the sixteen surrounding hells. It makes the number of hells in the list here sixteen.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":15,\"end\":215}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9293a655-33ec-43a7-a204-a4bcdaccc273\",\"sort\":88562,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.70\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“When they finally escape this condition, they will run away as best they can. Before them they will perceive a vast precipitous area filled with ravens, vultures, owls, and eagles, all with flaming beaks and claws. At this sight, the beings of this hell will faint and fall to the ground, yearning for safety and protection. The ravens, vultures, and owls will then descend upon them, tear all their limbs and organs apart with their flaming beaks and claws, and devour them. The beings of this hell will continue to be reborn in this way for many hundreds of thousands of years until finally their karmic actions have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted.\",\"label\":\"2.512\",\"sort\":8048,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"bd23cdcc-ffb7-4840-ae99-bbc2528134f2\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-775\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":125,\"uuid\":\"9293a655-33ec-43a7-a204-a4bcdaccc273\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“Eagle” is a provisional translation of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":40}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dhūmika\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"0a9bb978-db5d-42db-9502-6b7db9f3f288\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bya dhya mi ka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":69},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":69,\"uuid\":\"92f444a2-18ae-49b3-9cd2-2a32fabf9b29\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), which is a “smoke-colored” species of a bird of prey.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":69,\"end\":125}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"398f77ee-0738-4019-842d-b2e032824032\",\"sort\":88568,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.71\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘Their minds will be deluded And they will destroy two worlds. Alcohol is nothing but a fire That burns away the qualities of liberation.\",\"label\":\"2.555\",\"sort\":8474,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c787db7e-b8a0-4641-af5f-7812a7650910\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-820\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37,\"uuid\":\"398f77ee-0738-4019-842d-b2e032824032\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"I.e., their present and future lives.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ffd70e60-78bf-4bd0-bbfc-5dbaf2392172\",\"sort\":88570,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.72\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Truth is the beacon of all good qualities, The jewel-like delight of the wise, And the authentic path to higher realms‍— So is it lauded by those who are free from the fever.\",\"label\":\"2.592\",\"sort\":8899,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"02dcc927-5367-47fd-bfb1-af34640c531b\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-860\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"ffd70e60-78bf-4bd0-bbfc-5dbaf2392172\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"I.e., those free from the fever of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"afflictions\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":46},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a4b2555-d9c2-41b4-a5c0-2a8a0a115fa5\",\"uuid\":\"ecd6245b-18e2-486d-b9d7-101f94c4e66b\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":46,\"end\":47}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a0de5dd9-d522-45d3-a23a-82626b7ac1c2\",\"sort\":88574,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.73\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$3e\",\"label\":\"2.608\",\"sort\":9063,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"5edfb2ca-f177-42ec-b857-2fdf330be312\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-877\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":39,\"uuid\":\"a0de5dd9-d522-45d3-a23a-82626b7ac1c2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"rmog thag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":38},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":38,\"uuid\":\"9a1abe85-2558-47e9-a646-6521c022c785\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":39}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"809cf84f-1912-42e2-8d53-622ce834003e\",\"sort\":88578,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.74\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk who has knowledge of the effects of the ripening of karmic actions continues to examine the regions that surround the Great Howling Hell, he will perceive a hell realm known as Incomparable Harm. Inquiring into what completed and accumulated karmic actions may cause one to be born there, he will, as in the previous cases, see that such a birth is caused by resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing acts of killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, alcohol consumption, and lying. Thus, in order to amass land for the cultivation of sugarcane and other crops, certain people may employ lies and fraudulence to claim and steal away the land of others, such as the irrigation mounds that surround the fields. As in that way they deceive others with their lies, they will later, upon separating from their body, fall into the lower realms and take birth in the hell of Incomparable Harm.\",\"label\":\"2.613\",\"sort\":9128,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"29b4b505-13d7-4245-8b01-b2ac08432aff\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-883\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"809cf84f-1912-42e2-8d53-622ce834003e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here and in a similar passage below the Tibetan only mentions the “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":67}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Howling Hell\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":79},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7a28c7f9-6d3d-47c6-bf8c-14375613c412\",\"uuid\":\"a347efcf-4e3d-48ea-807a-31ff54a8df7c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":81}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6c3ec61e-638a-43bf-9014-0cdd73d2bf16\",\"sort\":88582,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.75\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The beings in that realm will experience the following tortures. Their skulls will be cleaved open from the top and their tongues will be cut off and extracted through the ensuing hole. This severance of the tongue will recur, because whenever their tongue is cut off, a new one will grow out in its place, only to be amputated again. Thus, until their negative acts have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted, their tongues will be cut off with flaming weapons throughout many hundreds of thousands of years.\",\"label\":\"2.617\",\"sort\":9188,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"50d2fb7c-3cd1-4619-b0d2-bebbca262171\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-888\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":49,\"uuid\":\"6c3ec61e-638a-43bf-9014-0cdd73d2bf16\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mtshon cha hu lu ka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":48},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":48,\"uuid\":\"446b77bc-c86e-442a-9d66-7b56df2dd3ca\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":49}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a8d66cc0-1351-44e1-9561-5f40ee836aea\",\"sort\":88586,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.76\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Next, the monk who has knowledge of the effects of the ripening of karmic actions will examine the neighboring region of the Great Howling Hell known as Blinding Smoke. Inquiring into what karmic actions may cause one to be born there, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and thus see that such a birth is caused by resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing acts of killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, and alcohol consumption. As for lying, in order to maximize their profit, there are businesspeople who falsely claim that a business agreement entitles them, and not others, to certain goods. In this way they manage to steal the goods through lies and treachery. Upon separating from their bodies, however, they will fall into the lower realms and be born in the hell of Blinding Smoke.\",\"label\":\"2.619\",\"sort\":9200,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"b7251c8c-3694-4473-82d8-07ad1700edcd\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-891\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":45,\"uuid\":\"a8d66cc0-1351-44e1-9561-5f40ee836aea\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Tibetan only mentions the “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":31}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Howling Hell\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":43},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7a28c7f9-6d3d-47c6-bf8c-14375613c412\",\"uuid\":\"f769ee5b-45d0-4f45-91e9-3a256364d9d7\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":45}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a5375eff-88dc-4f48-b475-7e9c194c7d91\",\"sort\":88590,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.77\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The beings in that realm will experience the following tortures. Just as in the case of the Reviving Hell and so forth, their extremely tender bodies will be cut asunder. The beings of this hell thus scream as all their major and minor body parts are chopped to bits. Yet in another fierce ripening that accords with their causal, negative acts, their tender bodies will reemerge whenever they have been cut up. While the beings of this hell are crying out, their bones remain sensitive even after six months. Then, from their bodies will appear multicolored worms that have vajra beaks and flaming mouths. They will gnaw on the bones and break them, thereby producing excruciating agony. This will continue for many hundreds of thousands of years until finally their negative acts have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted.\",\"label\":\"2.620\",\"sort\":9221,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"0b54449f-6d8f-4e12-8f4e-ea62766e96cf\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-893\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":164,\"uuid\":\"a5375eff-88dc-4f48-b475-7e9c194c7d91\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sems can dmyal ba pa de cho nges ’debs pa na/ zla ba drug lus pa’i rus pa gang yin pa de dag kyang rang gi lus las byung ba’i srin bu\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":162},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":162,\"uuid\":\"17920db5-cbc2-4824-a11e-c7e67c33982d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"….\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":162,\"end\":164}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9f8789b4-47be-4dc1-8a5a-dff5e84ce042\",\"sort\":88594,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.78\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk who has knowledge of the effects of the ripening of karmic actions continues to examine the regions that surround the Great Howling Hell, he will perceive a neighboring hell known as Instant Revival Upon Death. Inquiring into what karmic actions may cause one to be born there, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and thus see that such a birth is caused by resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing acts of killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, alcohol consumption, and lying. Based on such acts one will, when separating from one’s body, fall into the lower realms and be born in the hell of Instant Revival Upon Death.\",\"label\":\"2.626\",\"sort\":9279,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"f2b80d1c-fc71-45ba-8769-10815b69534e\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-900\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":60,\"uuid\":\"9f8789b4-47be-4dc1-8a5a-dff5e84ce042\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Above, this hell was named “Continuation of Life and Death.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":60}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0783cc01-4349-4e02-8656-250a373b1c93\",\"sort\":88596,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.79\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$3f\",\"label\":\"2.633\",\"sort\":9347,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"74df94e9-bfa2-4fca-b30f-49eace04749d\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-908\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"0783cc01-4349-4e02-8656-250a373b1c93\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"lus kyi lhag ma lus pa dag shin tu rgyug ste\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":73},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":73,\"uuid\":\"3323f5c7-692c-47e6-be3a-1ffd2f05cf0d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":73,\"end\":74}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9e09fe5b-baf7-4aaf-a087-c38a7a5949ba\",\"sort\":88600,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.80\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$40\",\"label\":\"2.635\",\"sort\":9369,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"dd33f139-13ee-44a6-8592-dd12cd301d50\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-911\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":46,\"uuid\":\"9e09fe5b-baf7-4aaf-a087-c38a7a5949ba\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Above, this hell was called “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Joyless Thought\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":44},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"51f99672-f56e-462b-974c-b922384423a9\",\"uuid\":\"bdcb32fa-065d-4710-a29e-51fedd922d23\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":44,\"end\":46}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"30bae374-bd76-4c23-a51b-3e820a4043a7\",\"sort\":88604,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.81\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk who has knowledge of the effects of the ripening of karmic actions continues to examine the regions that surround the Great Howling Hell, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and thus perceive that one is born there due to killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, and alcohol consumption, and lying. Moreover, when there is a dispute about wealth between two people who belong to the same class, or who share the same father and ancestors, some people may give false testimony motivated by a wish to deceive and blame others in order to side with one of the two disputants, or an uncle, or one side of the family. Those who knowingly carry out such complete acts, including their preparatory and conclusive stages, will, upon separating from their bodies, fall into the lower realms and take birth in the hell of Mutual Harm.\",\"label\":\"2.642\",\"sort\":9461,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"bbf519a4-8482-4056-8baf-31ccf88b96db\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-919\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":97,\"uuid\":\"30bae374-bd76-4c23-a51b-3e820a4043a7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brgyad pa’i blo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":44},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":44,\"uuid\":\"8b6b3678-ff74-4a9d-8726-9a6345663ad0\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Narthang: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":44,\"end\":56}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brgyud pa’i blo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":71},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":71,\"uuid\":\"2f0d935d-bc15-48c5-a509-a260307bf7af\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Kangxi: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":81}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brgyan pa’i blo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":96},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":96,\"uuid\":\"caa252a4-f141-4cfe-b12c-01cfd53af002\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":96,\"end\":97}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d48139d5-1f51-4b0a-9a80-7e406af864d9\",\"sort\":88612,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.82\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The beings in that realm will experience torture as they undergo the combined ordeals that are otherwise experienced in the hell of Reviving, and so forth. In particular, they will be held against a burning metal plate where weapons rain down on them so that their blood and flesh become like mush, or like kiṃśuka trees. The iron plate will thus become attached to their bodies. As the hell beings wail, the henchmen of the Lord of Death will then forcefully scrape off the flesh, fat, and blood that are now stuck to the metal plate.\",\"label\":\"2.646\",\"sort\":9518,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"4763ddc0-12cc-4e9f-b501-9736538343ba\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-924\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":108,\"uuid\":\"d48139d5-1f51-4b0a-9a80-7e406af864d9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. We have been unable to establish the precise nature of the following form of torture.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":108}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4194c807-50f8-40ac-9755-020a9d3d0d54\",\"sort\":88614,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.83\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$41\",\"label\":\"2.647\",\"sort\":9530,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"a772fd49-1254-480b-b1f8-3d419f6e05ed\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-927\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":127,\"uuid\":\"4194c807-50f8-40ac-9755-020a9d3d0d54\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The translation of this name follows the Sanskrit, reading \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":59}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kālāvelā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":67},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":67,\"uuid\":\"4b03d3be-a92b-4679-9462-ec28bd4de4c6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":71}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kālavelā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":79},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":79,\"uuid\":\"028a6d9f-6543-420c-b93c-d4cd0e54edd0\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":93}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gnod skyes\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":103},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":103,\"uuid\":\"e608bde5-7c80-43b3-9775-bc4f07c0658b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" suggests “Harm Arisen.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":103,\"end\":127}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fae71b2d-a20a-4f71-8637-bd80b80480f3\",\"sort\":88622,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.84\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The beings in that realm will experience torture as they undergo all the same ordeals that are otherwise experienced in the hell of Reviving, and so forth. In particular, they will have their eyes plucked out with flaming tongs. Those who have thus been blinded will then grow new, fresh, and most delicate eyes, and will thus be subjected to profuse torture. Their ears will be filled with boiling lead by the henchmen of the Lord of Death, who will also slash off their major and minor body parts with razors. So-called talalalalaka worms will enter their bowels and intestines and begin to feast on them.\",\"label\":\"2.654\",\"sort\":9622,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"2f7321ce-c8f0-45bd-8029-fe5d2571ed2d\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-935\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":171,\"uuid\":\"fae71b2d-a20a-4f71-8637-bd80b80480f3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mig ’dren pa dag gis drangs pa dang / de nas yang shin tu gzhon sha can sdug par skyes te/ gnod par ches mang ba dag gis de ’byin par byed do\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":170},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":170,\"uuid\":\"5322331b-0931-4ddf-a618-974c6e0aaac6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":170,\"end\":171}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5d75cd2e-7230-4f37-8690-570d4518a932\",\"sort\":88626,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.85\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The beings in that realm will experience torture as they undergo all the same ordeals that are otherwise experienced in the hell of Reviving, and so forth. In particular, they will have their eyes plucked out with flaming tongs. Those who have thus been blinded will then grow new, fresh, and most delicate eyes, and will thus be subjected to profuse torture. Their ears will be filled with boiling lead by the henchmen of the Lord of Death, who will also slash off their major and minor body parts with razors. So-called talalalalaka worms will enter their bowels and intestines and begin to feast on them.\",\"label\":\"2.654\",\"sort\":9622,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"2f7321ce-c8f0-45bd-8029-fe5d2571ed2d\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-935\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48,\"uuid\":\"5d75cd2e-7230-4f37-8690-570d4518a932\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"srin bu tA la la lwa la ka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":32},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":32,\"uuid\":\"6a8e8d35-d9d7-44f1-9b98-f85f89c11c9d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":32,\"end\":39}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tālūlaka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"9fbbdf46-0bde-4584-b0d2-7cb380c923d3\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":48}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a38090ff-a30f-472d-8b32-d643866d49a9\",\"sort\":88632,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.86\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“ ‘Truth will not come from anywhere else, And is not to be searched for elsewhere. Truth is the supreme place of pilgrimage‍— One that is not bound by holy water.\",\"label\":\"2.674\",\"sort\":9803,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3c19edc3-a518-462d-a0b3-6d7b225dc919\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-957\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":198,\"uuid\":\"a38090ff-a30f-472d-8b32-d643866d49a9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Places of pilgrimage (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tīrtha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":28},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":28,\"uuid\":\"30671a54-8c53-40a9-9925-d385fe3825ee\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), here meant figuratively, are usually on the banks of sacred rivers, hence the mention of “holy water” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":134}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tīrthasalila\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":134,\"end\":146},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":134,\"end\":146,\"uuid\":\"c8f9f151-7e3a-4719-9d1f-4d86b23b5794\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"˚). The translation of this verse remains tentative.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":198}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b618c45f-56e4-4efd-92b5-bdd541f4266a\",\"sort\":88638,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.87\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk who has knowledge of the effects of the ripening of karmic actions continues to examine the regions that surround the Great Howling Hell, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and thus perceive a neighboring hell known as Consuming Blood and Marrow. Inquiring into what karmic actions may cause one to be born in the hell of Consuming Blood and Marrow, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and see that such a birth is caused by completed and accumulated acts of killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, alcohol consumption, and lying. As for lying, certain kings, ministers, or other people in positions of authority may charge higher taxes than they are supposed to and yet claim that they are charging the correct amount. When they later separate from their bodies, they will fall into the lower realms and take birth in the hell of Consuming Blood and Fat.\",\"label\":\"2.697\",\"sort\":10014,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"f2ee19e6-6c92-45a2-897f-22bbb96c6c3c\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-981\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":55,\"uuid\":\"b618c45f-56e4-4efd-92b5-bdd541f4266a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Above, this hell was called \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Consuming Blood and Marrow\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":54},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2a2615ca-91e3-463e-ba9a-ba806705a585\",\"uuid\":\"00719f4b-4ef1-4872-aa36-a36f267b969c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":55}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1d9cad05-6368-43de-aa41-ab8dc01bbcdb\",\"sort\":88642,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.88\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Those who lied due to bias will now undergo all the same ordeals that are otherwise experienced in the hell of Reviving, and so forth‍—but intensified tenfold. Moreover, eleven bonfires will constantly emerge from their bodies, burning everywhere in the ten directions, and the tongues in the liars’ mouths will go starving and thirsting. Those who twisted the law in this way will constantly and in each moment take birth and burn. As they burn, they must undergo such sensations, and thus the hell of Eleven Flames cannot be even remotely compared to anything else. Until their negative acts have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted, their scorching and burning will continue in the hell of Eleven Flames for many hundreds of thousands of years.\",\"label\":\"2.703\",\"sort\":10083,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"e68d0414-28f8-41fc-bf00-35e6894bedb5\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-989\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":107,\"uuid\":\"1d9cad05-6368-43de-aa41-ab8dc01bbcdb\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gang me lce’i phung po bcu gcig po de dag ni bcu drug gi char yang mi phod do\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":106},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":106,\"uuid\":\"63908125-5ac1-4411-8714-a2a6b6b207d7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":106,\"end\":107}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4b43031b-b12b-45d3-9725-56404637db28\",\"sort\":88646,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.89\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$42\",\"label\":\"2.710\",\"sort\":10154,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"beaf6370-c715-4e0a-b23d-1463714f370c\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-997\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":88,\"uuid\":\"4b43031b-b12b-45d3-9725-56404637db28\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"We have been unable to identify the enumerations mentioned at the end of this paragraph.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":88}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7e2f655e-cad5-4546-b5b1-52b2c6f4a0ad\",\"sort\":88648,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.90\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$43\",\"label\":\"2.711\",\"sort\":10172,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"e1c220eb-316d-46f5-8b29-4f27a9250b57\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-999\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":66,\"uuid\":\"7e2f655e-cad5-4546-b5b1-52b2c6f4a0ad\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Reading \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":8}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’bying\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":8,\"end\":14},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":8,\"end\":14,\"uuid\":\"aaf38422-f6bd-42e6-b093-b4d3f49cd87a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (following the Yongle and Kangxi) instead of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":14,\"end\":60}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’byin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":65},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":65,\"uuid\":\"3b410dd8-d09d-4628-bf1e-ca7f1945240c\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":65,\"end\":66}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"53251fd5-9c4f-46bf-bfa2-93e156ac8686\",\"sort\":88654,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.91\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$44\",\"label\":\"2.717\",\"sort\":10267,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1b9684e4-2ba8-4137-bf93-1151d7e67949\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1006\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":159,\"uuid\":\"53251fd5-9c4f-46bf-bfa2-93e156ac8686\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé here transliterates the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":38}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"pippalaka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"67367eb0-2e7b-4f7d-b1cf-a734986d29f8\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":50}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pib pa la ka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":63},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":63,\"uuid\":\"cafcb954-dee0-4d8e-947d-f155aada5c76\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":69}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sūcaka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":69,\"end\":75},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":69,\"end\":75,\"uuid\":\"cdd33081-3802-45b7-976a-74fb92a41d22\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":75,\"end\":79}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"su tsa ka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":88},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":88,\"uuid\":\"d73d0f75-9fc3-48b4-b738-4fed52c54f8d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The two terms can be translated, respectively, as “pin” and “needle.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":159}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5c64e4dd-6a49-43e2-be56-b3d01f0181bf\",\"sort\":88664,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.92\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$45\",\"label\":\"2.717\",\"sort\":10267,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1b9684e4-2ba8-4137-bf93-1151d7e67949\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1006\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"5c64e4dd-6a49-43e2-be56-b3d01f0181bf\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e5fd6191-0655-4851-a153-b48fec47e59d\",\"sort\":88666,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.93\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$46\",\"label\":\"2.717\",\"sort\":10267,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"1b9684e4-2ba8-4137-bf93-1151d7e67949\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1006\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23,\"uuid\":\"e5fd6191-0655-4851-a153-b48fec47e59d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"snying gi lam la\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":22},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"b4182e38-6e26-4932-aef4-d6891bb622da\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":23}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cf4950ec-a9d9-40b9-9ab7-954454e7e902\",\"sort\":88670,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.94\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“As the monk who has knowledge of the effects of the ripening of karmic actions continues to examine the regions that surround the Hell of Heat, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and thus perceive a neighboring realm known as Teeming with Snakes. Inquiring into what karmic actions may cause one to be born there, he will apply knowledge derived from hearing and see that such a birth is caused by resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing acts of killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, alcohol consumption, and lying. As for resorting to, becoming habituated to, and increasing wrong view, some people teach that, ‘If you assume a squatting position, drink, and slurp from your hand, you will achieve the transcendence of suffering. That attainment is not the result of giving up desire, anger, and ignorance, nor is it due to serenity of the senses.’ When later such people separate from their bodies, they will fall into the lower realms and be born in the hell known as Teeming with Snakes.\",\"label\":\"2.731\",\"sort\":10435,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7b5598e0-f584-4e34-bdb0-fad3313caeb0\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1024\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":98,\"uuid\":\"cf4950ec-a9d9-40b9-9ab7-954454e7e902\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"cog cog por bsgyings par ’dug la skom ’thung zhing lag pa la ldag pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":97},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":97,\"uuid\":\"65d110ff-675e-4062-bd9b-c800b1ccfc07\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":97,\"end\":98}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f8667537-82e7-48db-9041-3e795e488925\",\"sort\":88674,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.95\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“When after a very long time they succeed in escaping from these fishes’ mouths, they will next enter a pot of boiling copper. As soon as they sink into it, infinitely poisonous insects called ‘burning forest flies’ with fangs as sharp as diamonds will attack. Within the darkness of the pot of boiling copper, their bodies will thus be reduced to powder and the worms will consume every last morsel. If they scream in pain, their mouths will fill up with suffocating, boiling copper. All their body-orifices will likewise fill up with molten copper and will be blocked, cooked, and torn apart. Thus, they must keep swimming in the molten copper for a very long time. As they swim, razor-like winds produced by karma will rise. Until their negative acts have finally been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted, these winds will keep pulverizing the bodies of those who spoke wrongly by deceiving others regarding karmic actions and their effects.\",\"label\":\"2.736\",\"sort\":10499,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7f7e3e19-e940-4377-ab43-5b7c93013d67\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1030\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":95,\"uuid\":\"f8667537-82e7-48db-9041-3e795e488925\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"srin bu a ba mA si ka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":27},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":27,\"uuid\":\"525f02f1-f011-4c01-992c-089231f14214\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The translation is based on reading the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":78}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"māsikā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":84},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":84,\"uuid\":\"1228cda5-baa5-4dfb-a1d8-e676abd8a68e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":88}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mācikā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":94},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":94,\"uuid\":\"e5a15832-6189-4da9-93d5-cd01da673954\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":95}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"185ab9e8-6afe-4559-bd08-85d63475ec2d\",\"sort\":88682,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.96\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$47\",\"label\":\"2.738\",\"sort\":10521,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"b6d96fb1-dd83-4bde-ab1e-f370232a72de\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1033\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":61,\"uuid\":\"185ab9e8-6afe-4559-bd08-85d63475ec2d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"skye ba’i bar du byed pa yin te\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":60},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":60,\"uuid\":\"8c1b969e-e964-4687-8d84-3ee196269ff4\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":61}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6167a6d0-c61f-4e2f-bcdd-d5c6e136f741\",\"sort\":88686,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.97\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$48\",\"label\":\"2.739\",\"sort\":10547,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"befa684a-17aa-4854-9de5-ea8db4cae624\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1035\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":103,\"uuid\":\"6167a6d0-c61f-4e2f-bcdd-d5c6e136f741\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Based on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bskol ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":21,\"uuid\":\"226f4112-9c8d-44e4-ae4f-8b6ec842299b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" that appears in Choné, Lithang, Narthang, Yongle, and Lhasa. Degé reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":94}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bskor ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":102},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":102,\"uuid\":\"bddcebc6-96d2-454c-8035-00a9959d0348\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":102,\"end\":103}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"46b6f8bd-5714-430e-b79a-59c8752fe58b\",\"sort\":88692,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.98\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“When henchmen of the Lord of Death come by, the upper and lower openings of the vase will be sealed, so that the hell beings within cannot escape. The henchmen of the Lord of Death think, ‘We must seal this vase with vajra-like plaster and torture the beings here in various ways without giving them any chance of escape.’ Further, they will think, ‘We shall engulf this vase, which is produced by karma, with garlands of flames, and so double the temperature within it.’ Thus, they proceed with their torture, intensifying the heat of the vase by feeding the flames with iron fuel. The hell beings will float to the surface, boiling in molten copper and inflicting harm upon one another. Tortured and miserable in numerous ways, they continue to disintegrate, or be boiled and burned by the poisonous snake fangs, until finally their negative karmic actions have been overcome, relinquished, and exhausted.\",\"label\":\"2.740\",\"sort\":10559,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c018bf61-016c-441a-beea-9e312b21cecc\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1037\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":102,\"uuid\":\"46b6f8bd-5714-430e-b79a-59c8752fe58b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Based on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"brkyang nul\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":24},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":24,\"uuid\":\"171cb471-a5ec-436b-a323-ac2d4ba34e9b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" that appears in Kangxi, Lithang, Narthang, and Yongle. Degé reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":24,\"end\":91}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"skyong nul\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":91,\"end\":101},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":91,\"end\":101,\"uuid\":\"62441048-4954-4377-98b9-acebda096306\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":101,\"end\":102}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"74948a29-80be-4af0-ac90-5afc16693c12\",\"sort\":88698,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.99\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$49\",\"label\":\"2.747\",\"sort\":10628,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"cdf25c11-06d3-401a-8cd9-654134d63840\",\"workUuid\":\"b3a4a1c4-86b6-4e02-83f9-01c6b14cf835\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-068-021-1045\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":100,\"uuid\":\"74948a29-80be-4af0-ac90-5afc16693c12\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation of “fleas, or bedbugs” is tentative. Degé: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"srog chags mar ko Ta ka’am rkang la za ba’am\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":99},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":99,\"uuid\":\"99fcb97f-f7a2-4b26-846a-5cde6ab00b67\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":100}}]}]}],\"glossary\":[{\"uuid\":\"4c915ddd-5405-45b1-afdd-85b8638b8488\",\"authority\":\"b78b004b-13a3-4e41-94a8-dc41f310f7bd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eRefers to \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9044\\\"\u003eEncircled by a Thousand Houses\u003c/span\u003e in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9544\\\"\u003eOrnament of the Mind\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"A Thousand Houses\",\"tibetan\":\"ཁང་བུ་སྟོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"khang bu stong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7114b873-5be9-4a36-a988-e6af036a6bf2\",\"authority\":\"2b5fc345-e542-4ebb-8575-de0f75031e84\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn Indian \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8569\\\"\u003epaṇḍita\u003c/span\u003e involved in translating this \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9986\\\"\u003esūtra\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abhayākaragupta\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་བྷ་ཡ་ཀ་ར་གུཔྟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhayā­kara­gupta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a bha ya ka ra gup+ta\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3591dede-6897-432f-94e9-ea797987a9bc\",\"authority\":\"47fb5241-a816-4a41-9cab-35c2116593f3\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe Buddha’s teachings regarding subjects such as wisdom, psychology, metaphysics, and cosmology.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abhidharma\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་མངོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhidharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos mngon pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7d3892fd-428b-4793-80f2-5a946f452090\",\"authority\":\"e476bfe8-56c3-4a97-869c-63b0e813626c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA mountain near the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8489\\\"\u003easura\u003c/span\u003e city \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9012\\\"\u003eDouble Pleasure\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abhrakrama Summit\",\"tibetan\":\"རྩེ་མོ་ལྷང་ཚེར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhrakrama\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtse mo lhang tsher\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d3a4e122-6eda-43da-8b23-0c200e3cdb34\",\"authority\":\"5bb8f692-a1dd-4f55-b9b7-76d93fa3d19a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA city in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9209\\\"\u003eGodānīya\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abhrakūṭa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་བྷྲ་ཀཱུ་ཊཱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhrakūṭa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a bhra kU TA\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0f4647d9-87a1-42ef-b904-2f27cfa08dc4\",\"authority\":\"362a3fe1-9b3c-40a0-8937-1f3244a502f5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn ancient title given to ascetics, monks, hermits, and saints, namely, those who have attained the realization of a truth through their own contemplation and not by divine revelation. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eHere also used as a specific epithet of the buddhas.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"able one\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐུབ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"muni\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thub\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cbfef027-e86c-4a20-bb28-e2dfb04a3f3a\",\"authority\":\"73835e97-00af-429f-8876-4380b15cee31\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA pool in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9036\\\"\u003eDwelling on the Disk\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abode of Water\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆུ་གནས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chu gnas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6684be0d-4a7a-4862-b04b-4160d4aeae60\",\"authority\":\"689ccc05-fbf4-4572-838f-eb6373ace250\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe four \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003eabodes of Brahmā\u003c/span\u003e are love, compassion, joy, and equanimity.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"abodes of Brahmā\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པའི་གནས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmavihāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs pa’i gnas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2b4fd96b-604d-4913-b81a-9ca7bcbc2306\",\"authority\":\"86f27aff-cf23-4aac-8332-0d9d356356db\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn ocean far beyond \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abounding with Jewels\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་པོ་ཆེ་རྣམས་ཀྱིས་ཀུན་ཏུ་གང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin po che rnams kyis kun tu gang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3023de43-79da-4d7f-9a47-65514184056c\",\"authority\":\"8d2b435f-aa30-4ece-b923-f6f9e96c8c56\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA mountain in the sea south of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abrikṣabho\",\"tibetan\":\"འབྲི་ཥ་བྷོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abrikṣabho\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’bri Sha b+ho\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1118ecdd-986d-450c-a7b7-931fbc5bbd01\",\"authority\":\"862f7ef0-33ed-4a8f-8536-739e51283479\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA mountain between \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9209\\\"\u003eGodānīya\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9847\\\"\u003eVideha\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abundance\",\"tibetan\":\"ལེགས་པར་གང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"legs par gang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7e2b8e3c-f677-4e03-8851-36a52799c8bd\",\"authority\":\"a35cde60-d38d-4c05-a432-5a724e738dd8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA river on \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9657\\\"\u003eSaṅkāśa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abundant Kūrma Monsters\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆུ་སྲིན་ཀཱུ་རྨ་མང་བ་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chu srin kU rma mang ba nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"dc73dc0d-f0fc-40fb-a1a0-f9af2af8c352\",\"authority\":\"ac399b1d-e7d6-4b87-adf1-043899d718b8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn island in the sea west of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Abundant Lions\",\"tibetan\":\"སེང་གེས་ཀུན་ནེས་གང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"seng ges kun nes gang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fac3387c-9067-4dfb-85bf-74236be0f60c\",\"authority\":\"27a7741e-a641-4d4e-ba70-3b996b45ee88\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eKing at the second level of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8489\\\"\u003easuras\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Acala\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྟན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"acala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brtan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2087a221-01ff-4546-af43-54cc08f2b411\",\"authority\":\"4a9e41c5-ee82-46e3-9ea0-719cc7310c6d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA conditioned factor that according to Sarvāstivāda \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9985\\\"\u003eAbhidharma\u003c/span\u003e is responsible for the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8583\\\"\u003eripening\u003c/span\u003e of karmic actions subsequent to their having been performed. See also \u003ca href=\\\"end-notes.xhtml#UT22084-068-021-433\\\" data-pointer-type=\\\"id\\\"\u003en.35\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"acquisition\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐོབ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prāpti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thob pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"017e281b-0374-44df-b134-8dae8c36c9ea\",\"authority\":\"be29e099-49cc-4779-96db-bae93dc29d84\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA forest in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9026\\\"\u003eDwelling in Forests\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Action\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་སྤྱོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun spyod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"494d1933-5e79-4bb8-bd99-7a8b24a1cd90\",\"authority\":\"504f09e9-f0b8-4f04-b2db-3b1ab97090ea\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA realm of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8617\\\"\u003etriple-lute-bearer gods\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Activity\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་སྤྱོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam spyod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b59b805c-4cb5-4883-a807-21fe6012f460\",\"authority\":\"cde5b0c8-71fe-427b-90bb-4ec2c3032352\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIndian \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8569\\\"\u003epaṇḍita\u003c/span\u003e referred to in the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9986\\\"\u003esūtra\u003c/span\u003e’s colophon\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aḍitacandra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་ཌི་ཏ་ཙནྡྲ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aḍitacandra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a Di ta tsan+d+ra\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2b221652-979d-481e-b12f-1cca45de85d8\",\"authority\":\"f9d5a771-cd7c-4166-9241-422a3fb88afa\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA forest of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8489\\\"\u003easuras\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Adorned\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spras pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9c4c8b61-ab51-4654-8ba9-6db41414ee5b\",\"authority\":\"7086ff0d-0ee5-4ea8-96e6-e0b3254ff91d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA previous ruler of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9276\\\"\u003eHeaven of the Thirty-Three\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Adorned with Glorious Garlands\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟི་བརྗིད་ཕྲེང་ལྡན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzi brjid phreng ldan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3ecf595f-fca5-471d-8237-d39bf02812d7\",\"authority\":\"1b8ae12f-7d22-49fb-be73-3ac3d0a488ae\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA river on \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9657\\\"\u003eSaṅkāśa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Adorned with Musāragalva\",\"tibetan\":\"མུ་ས་ར་གལྦ་རྒྱན་དུ་བྱས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mu sa ra galba rgyan du byas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"976c78d3-1d7d-4170-bc23-0eae01a0f613\",\"authority\":\"ebb70789-cc53-42e2-b83d-b4883d4973b5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA mountain in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9672\\\"\u003eShining in Manifold Ways\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Adorned with Numerous Cascades\",\"tibetan\":\"འབབ་ཆུ་རྣམ་པ་སྣ་ཚོགས་པ་དང་ལྡན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’bab chu rnam pa sna tshogs pa dang ldan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"36c8a62f-eb14-4087-9c0f-ab6c97d92bb1\",\"authority\":\"fc703393-940a-4667-bd47-243dee773d5e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn emanated mountain on the trunk of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8636\\\"\u003eAirāvaṇa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Adorned with Springs\",\"tibetan\":\"འབྱུང་ཁུངས་ཀྱི་བརྒྱན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’byung khungs kyi brgyan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f8912612-1470-4d65-9008-4c3badb0c43c\",\"authority\":\"d27c234a-90f4-48a0-887f-b664aecc99ad\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA river on \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9657\\\"\u003eSaṅkāśa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Adūva\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་ཌུ་བཱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"adūva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a Du bA\"}},{\"uuid\":\"71008734-7212-40a4-8292-af02beb73b8d\",\"authority\":\"3cedde9a-08d1-4c49-95fd-fbc033f6ee80\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of sixteen realms that surround the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9279\\\"\u003eHell of Ultimate Torment\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Advancing Fire\",\"tibetan\":\"འགྲོ་བ་མེས་འཇིག, འགྲོ་བ་མེས་སྲེག\",\"sanskrit\":\"caṅkramāṇāgni­dāha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’gro ba mes sreg, ’gro ba mes ’jig\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9a4b2555-d9c2-41b4-a5c0-2a8a0a115fa5\",\"authority\":\"c87671dd-3ffd-410d-a94d-fca04ee8ccc2\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eLiterally “pain,” “torment,” or “\u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003eaffliction\u003c/span\u003e.” In Buddhist Hybrid Sanskrit it literally means “impurity” or “depravity.” In its technical use in Buddhism it means any negative quality in the mind that causes continued existence in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9884\\\"\u003esaṃsāra\u003c/span\u003e. There are the 84,000 variations of mental disturbances for which the 84,000 categories of the Buddha’s teachings serve as the antidote. These mental disturbances can be subsumed into the three or five poisons of attachment, aversion, and ignorance plus arrogance and jealousy.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"affliction\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉོན་མོངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kleśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyon mongs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"85d2e03b-5740-407c-bd6b-39265543ee3b\",\"authority\":\"4f09e3ef-8eb9-402b-84e7-7e762100fc0b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn the context of this \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9986\\\"\u003esūtra\u003c/span\u003e, this appears to refer to the “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8483\\\"\u003eage of perfection\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"age of excellence\",\"tibetan\":\"བཟང་ལྡན་གྱི་དུས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bzang ldan gyi dus\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0d768242-00f0-454c-ab1d-bda8b119a81b\",\"authority\":\"43a1745c-8450-47fb-9d0e-0e61858f4e7d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe first of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-10017\\\"\u003efour ages\u003c/span\u003e of human life in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e. Humans in this age enjoy good qualities such as long lifespans free from disease (see \u003ca href=\\\"UT22084-068-021-chapter-8.xhtml#UT22084-068-021-8228\\\" data-pointer-type=\\\"id\\\"\u003e5.238\u003c/a\u003e). Over the course of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-10017\\\"\u003efour ages\u003c/span\u003e humans will lose a quarter of these qualities between each age.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"age of perfection\",\"tibetan\":\"རྫོགས་ལྡན་གྱི་དུས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kṛtayuga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rdzogs ldan gyi dus\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a3701720-b643-4651-b78a-76ec8d56aaf5\",\"authority\":\"691a1a07-bc0d-49aa-b421-58461e6bab8a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe last of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-10017\\\"\u003efour ages\u003c/span\u003e of human life in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e. In this age humans are endowed with only one remaining quarter of the good qualities that they had during the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8483\\\"\u003eage of perfection\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"age of strife\",\"tibetan\":\"རྩོད་ལྡན་གྱི་དུས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kaliyuga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtsod ldan gyi dus\"}},{\"uuid\":\"76bfadf2-98bf-41e2-a8fa-8f76513d0e47\",\"authority\":\"d57a6b6b-ea2b-4de6-942f-0153e6fac30d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe second of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-10017\\\"\u003efour ages\u003c/span\u003e of human life in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e. In this age humans are endowed with three quarters of the good qualities that they had during the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8483\\\"\u003eage of perfection\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"age of threefold endowment, threefold endowment\",\"tibetan\":\"གསུམ་ལྡན་གྱི་དུས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tretayuga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gsum ldan gyi dus\"}},{\"uuid\":\"501c9b2d-f935-48bf-8735-d3ea86d126e4\",\"authority\":\"bf7375ac-4e4d-4f0b-a3fc-50db59905d97\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe third of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-10017\\\"\u003efour ages\u003c/span\u003e of human life in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e. In this age humans are endowed with two quarters, or half of the good qualities that they had during the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8483\\\"\u003eage of perfection\u003c/span\u003e. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"age of twofold endowment, twofold\",\"tibetan\":\"གཉིས་ལྡན་གྱི་དུས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dvāparayuga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnyis ldan gyi dus\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b43ca2c1-a3b3-4ed9-b5f9-520b1b5ed114\",\"authority\":\"befb80a6-3a70-411f-84f4-2016cc3a88fa\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe five psycho-physical components of personal experience: form, feeling, perception, formations, and consciousness.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"aggregate\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕུང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"skandha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"phung po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5015ae4f-98db-492b-b39e-0064362dc4e0\",\"authority\":\"1a1bcc75-c13f-4d4c-9ede-cfabc06733ff\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bird that we have been unable to identify.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"agnicūḍa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨག་ནི་ཙུ་ཌ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"agnicūḍa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ag ni tsu Da\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e34669f1-0ab4-4450-9f2a-4f0e1a0e197b\",\"authority\":\"add04ae2-79d8-472c-a098-c38ca8d6a366\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA righteous \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8562\\\"\u003enāga\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ahi\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་འགྲོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ahi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun ’gro\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bfac64f6-47d3-4e7f-93bf-b6a403f30b46\",\"authority\":\"f9af7957-81bb-4bb4-a09d-33690a95dcc0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8738\\\"\u003eŚakra\u003c/span\u003e’s elephant.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Airāvaṇa\",\"tibetan\":\"ས་སྲུང་གི་བུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"airāvaṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sa srung gi bu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"054d4525-ad0a-4d70-ab79-01f35bc4c8ac\",\"authority\":\"b453535f-79df-4862-95ac-94cf5fb83a63\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA realm that neighbors the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9278\\\"\u003eHell of Intense Heat\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Alala\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་ལ་ལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ṭaṭaṭaṭa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a la la\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d2c12afc-be10-4612-b98c-53bf5a22bfe5\",\"authority\":\"06ab39d2-f356-47fd-9206-18ba791e8054\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA forest upon \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9575\\\"\u003eMount Playful\u003c/span\u003e in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9734\\\"\u003eSudharma\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"All Seasons\",\"tibetan\":\"དུས་ཚིགས་ཐམས་ཅད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dus tshigs thams cad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0e76a5bb-9397-4548-a23b-0308b5c69c5f\",\"authority\":\"5d10fe77-9476-45ed-a2d8-03da7ac098d4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA town in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9847\\\"\u003eVideha\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"All the People\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐྱེ་བོ་ཐམས་ཅད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skye bo thams cad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e1998ba4-9747-4516-81a0-25485de5d175\",\"authority\":\"c0740839-c0d7-4159-a298-c0b50a4ef71d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA summit in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9544\\\"\u003eOrnament of the Mind\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"All Worlds\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇིག་རྟེན་ཐམས་ཅད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jig rten thams cad pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7b357867-d2f5-4ed6-8c3b-3b8ca15e14f8\",\"authority\":\"8cf290e5-541d-4d2a-a938-5bfc0251b896\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA river on \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9657\\\"\u003eSaṅkāśa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"All-Reaching\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉེ་འཁོར་ན་ཁྱབ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nye ’khor na khyab pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"04bccafd-3cc4-42b2-a249-07b6649932ba\",\"authority\":\"642c3f63-111f-478e-9d67-f1ac6f72031a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe sharing of merit as food, drink, etc. is offered to members of the saṅgha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"alms\",\"tibetan\":\"བསོད་སྙོམས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"piṇḍapāta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsod snyoms\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cdbc113a-61da-44e6-98b1-01e57d0c83ad\",\"authority\":\"a92345ba-540a-453d-a5e4-3b5b2d9de996\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(1) A forest of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8489\\\"\u003easuras\u003c/span\u003e. (2) A grove in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9403\\\"\u003eLateral\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Always Delightful\",\"tibetan\":\"རྟག་ཏུ་ཉམས་དགའ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtag tu nyams dga’\"}},{\"uuid\":\"35fc0557-97e2-44f1-b3f9-77a3dae381db\",\"authority\":\"40c9de19-e191-419f-9fe1-a48226a4bb3c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(1) A park in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9757\\\"\u003eSustained by Fruition\u003c/span\u003e (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ertag tu dga’ ba\u003c/em\u003e). (2) A pleasure grove in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9283\\\"\u003eHigh Conduct\u003c/span\u003e (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ertag tu dga’ ba\u003c/em\u003e). (3) A pond on \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9078\\\"\u003eEqual Peaks\u003c/span\u003e (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ertag tu mngon par dga’ ba\u003c/em\u003e). (4) A forest of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8489\\\"\u003easuras\u003c/span\u003e (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003etin di kun dga’\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Always Joyous\",\"tibetan\":\"ཏིན་དི་ཀུན་དགའ།, རྟག་ཏུ་དགའ་བ།, རྟག་ཏུ་མངོན་པར་དགའ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtag tu dga’ ba, rtag tu mngon par dga’ ba, tin di kun dga’\"}},{\"uuid\":\"449eedcc-a3e7-49ba-963f-6d7b9a4b6fca\",\"authority\":\"2c02baf4-0ece-4579-8f66-c49bcc21f21f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA major śrāvaka disciple and personal attendant of the Buddha Śākyamuni during the last twenty-five years of his life. He was a cousin of the Buddha (according to the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eMahāvastu\u003c/cite\u003e, he was a son of Śuklodana, one of the brothers of King Śuddhodana, which means he was a brother of Devadatta; other sources say he was a son of Amṛtodana, another brother of King Śuddhodana, which means he would have been a brother of Aniruddha).\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eĀnanda, having always been in the Buddha’s presence, is said to have memorized all the teachings he heard and is celebrated for having recited all the Buddha’s teachings by memory at the first council of the Buddhist saṅgha, thus preserving the teachings after the Buddha’s parinirvāṇa. The phrase “Thus did I hear at one time,” found at the beginning of the sūtras, usually stands for his recitation of the teachings. He became a patriarch after the passing of Mahākāśyapa.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ānanda\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་དགའ་བོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ānanda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun dga’ bo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c1dafb18-55e7-411b-b562-92dce8fc1bc0\",\"authority\":\"9633950b-153d-4206-a55c-7f2b2702cf7f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA lake near Mount \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9739\\\"\u003eSumeru\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anavatapta\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་དྲོས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anavatapta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma dros pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"07cf595b-f510-4e65-91fe-6509c1dcb4cf\",\"authority\":\"be243857-a3ac-4fef-b24a-ed5df72d4263\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eUnidentified region of India.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Andhaka\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨན་དྷ་ཀ\",\"sanskrit\":\"andhaka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"an dha ka\"}},{\"uuid\":\"735976cb-b5c9-4885-b73d-f5bf6f511794\",\"authority\":\"a460060c-cbdc-4c7f-9dc5-3aa34575a44b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA land in the east of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aṅga\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨང་ག\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṅga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ang ga\"}},{\"uuid\":\"49e78f8f-4702-4a65-846b-a7e3bc5ee165\",\"authority\":\"9186700b-96ce-4c50-8fcc-9bbe2139afe4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the five or six classes of sentient beings, who suffer from gross ignorance or bewilderment (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003egti mug\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003emoha\u003c/em\u003e). They inhabit the realm of desire along with human beings.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"animal\",\"tibetan\":\"དུད་འགྲོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tīryak\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dud ’gro\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e3d81638-947d-4188-9fb0-ab85855682c1\",\"authority\":\"b38dbe52-ff77-449f-a035-8454fca452f2\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA city in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9209\\\"\u003eGodānīya\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aṇira\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་ཎི་ར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṇira\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a Ni ra\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1a7267b1-d939-421f-9507-9bf6288a9835\",\"authority\":\"472eb581-a8a4-431f-989c-fc32f8bc7ad3\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA land in the east of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Antelope Dress\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣ་བ་གོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rna ba gon pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f4c608f9-c127-4e00-a800-8ce5f8764db7\",\"authority\":\"f72abff0-90f1-4817-b264-a297c7d8c983\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA mountain in the east of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anūna\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨ་ནཱུ་ན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anūna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"a nU na\"}},{\"uuid\":\"59d43f84-2a07-48ff-9606-bdf201718ef0\",\"authority\":\"3aa68974-0d5c-4039-963c-702ba6fc1e03\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA lake on \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9078\\\"\u003eEqual Peaks\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Any Taste You Like\",\"tibetan\":\"ཇི་ལྟར་འདོད་པའི་རོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ji ltar ’dod pa’i ro\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c0be66a6-adef-4076-bfed-1bd31a062e33\",\"authority\":\"f8c54959-d6f4-4351-b919-d91f63ddb5eb\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA mountain in the sea west of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ardhamaru\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨར་དྷ་མ་རུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ardhamaru\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ar dha ma ru\"}},{\"uuid\":\"122343bb-ba85-456e-a6df-169cee92fb80\",\"authority\":\"8fdb3f59-986d-4576-b980-dcdec82c1252\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA lake on \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9078\\\"\u003eEqual Peaks\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Arjuna\",\"tibetan\":\"ཨརྫུ་ནཿ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"arjuna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ardzu naH\"}},{\"uuid\":\"78d9dcf5-719c-4c3b-a32a-789690f496f4\",\"authority\":\"15d4983f-a5bf-430b-bfca-b35b22b49859\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA land to the north of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9338\\\"\u003eJambudvīpa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Army of Heroes\",\"tibetan\":\"དཔའ་བོའི་སྡེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dpa’ bo’i sde\"}},{\"uuid\":\"95f18d83-afa5-4646-80ae-c72d5927b0ab\",\"authority\":\"1d96ec3a-8076-4d8b-ae9d-39a3b90a17fa\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eSaraca asoca\u003c/em\u003e. The aromatic blossoms of this plant are clustered together as orange, yellow, and red bunches of petals.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"aśoka\",\"tibetan\":\"མྱ་ངན་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aśoka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mya ngan med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f12d9c95-4b6d-442c-ac5b-7fd1c7794f19\",\"authority\":\"14fcc226-483e-4a0d-bd02-e0b2cb1c267e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThese are impermanence, suffering, emptiness, absence of self, origination, causality, production, conditionality, cessation, peace, excellence, deliverance, path, reason, practice, and release. See \u003ca href=\\\"UT22084-068-021-section-6.xhtml#UT22084-068-021-4133\\\" data-pointer-type=\\\"id\\\"\u003e4.B.1188\u003c/a\u003e for an explanation of these.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"aspects of the four truths of noble beings, sixteen aspects, sixteen aspects (of the four truths of noble beings)\",\"tibetan\":\"བདེན་བཞིའི་དཔྱོད་པ་རྣམ་པ་བཅུ་དྲུག, བདེན་བཞིའི་རྣམ་པ་བཅུ་དྲུག\",\"sanskrit\":\"ṣoḍaśākāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bden bzhi’i dpyod pa rnam pa bcu drug, bden bzhi’i rnam pa bcu drug\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5f1024e5-d735-4094-89c8-9a8baec55fd2\",\"authority\":\"32837dd6-edd0-49d4-b729-9e3e243c4fa1\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA type of nonhuman being whose precise status is subject to different views, but is included as one of the six classes of beings in the sixfold classification of realms of rebirth. In the Buddhist context, asuras are powerful beings said to be dominated by envy, ambition, and hostility. They are also known in the pre-Buddhist and pre-Vedic mythologies of India and Iran, and feature prominently in Vedic and post-Vedic Brahmanical mythology, as well as in the Buddhist tradition. In these traditions, asuras are often described as being engaged in interminable conflict with the devas (gods).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"asura\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷ་མ་ཡིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asura\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lha ma yin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9ab99c71-ad21-4eb7-9f2b-d5efe40fb64e\",\"authority\":\"7a0c3b8a-6bf3-4db6-b830-c9b52b7580ba\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA female \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8489\\\"\u003easura\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"asurī\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷ་མ་ཡིན་གྱི་བུ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asurī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lha ma yin gyi bu mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"db390ea4-e611-4052-9e54-cfa2f47b6f1c\",\"authority\":\"f45db354-5e82-40e9-8f1f-d2eac50f83ed\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn unvirtuous \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8562\\\"\u003enāga\u003c/span\u003e king.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aṭopa\",\"tibetan\":\"བསྒྱིངས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṭopa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsgyings pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"41933dd3-edec-432a-bdb8-59b69e595161\",\"authority\":\"02c169f0-78a6-4458-b668-6fa79d48de5e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA realm inhabited by \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8530\\\"\u003egarland-bearer gods\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Attached to Objects\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡུལ་ལ་ཆགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yul la chags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5ea36316-13ef-49c8-a58c-b367a13e5452\",\"authority\":\"c4c23f6b-bead-4675-8ec9-1a73666aba23\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA realm inhabited by \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8530\\\"\u003egarland-bearer gods\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Attached to Pleasures\",\"tibetan\":\"འདོད་པ་ལ་ཆགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’dod pa la chags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c689f598-567d-48db-b270-ac1fd5d68918\",\"authority\":\"4dff2194-f9c4-47bd-8805-b2f8d8c79c5a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA realm of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8621\\\"\u003evessel-bearer gods\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Attached to Smell\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲི་ལ་ཆགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dri la chags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"64094fd8-df42-4c66-84d1-8bfb06e31e4a\",\"authority\":\"f3753e63-cf4b-40e9-b38c-cd53086fb7a9\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA realm of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8621\\\"\u003evessel-bearer gods\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Attached to Sound\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྲ་ལ་ཆགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgra la chags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"534ca811-b034-4eeb-8c02-5d8341e3855d\",\"authority\":\"46636ee1-2d7f-4430-afdb-02886c4f9143\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA realm of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-8617\\\"\u003etriple-lute-bearer gods\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Attached to That\",\"tibetan\":\"དེ་ལ་ཆགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"de la chags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"288b51a8-a353-41cf-a0e4-b1275e277d99\",\"authority\":\"3a35aa31-2d5f-42d6-bdfc-aaf22aa9015c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA city in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-068-021-9209\\\"\u003eGodānīya\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Attraction\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་སོང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems song ba\"}},{